"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487142","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Culture White Paper published last month makes clear that this Government is committed to ensuring that the arts should be an essential part of every child’s education both in and out of school. This includes working with the Department for Education on a range of music and cultural education programmes since 2012, supporting the Arts Council’s Cultural Education Challenge to create a network of cultural education partnerships and a new Cultural Citizens programme which will be piloted in three areas to support the engagement of disadvantaged young people with arts and culture in their local community.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-11T08:55:26.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487142/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487142/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-24","Arts: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to maximise engagement of children and young people in the arts.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","32663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487143","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) has no plans to extend the period of time in which separating spouses of Service personnel have to vacate MOD provided accommodation. However, the current 93-day period can be extended further according to individual circumstances, such as children's schooling, relevant welfare and any medical considerations.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-04-11T15:47:16.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487143/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487143/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487143/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-24","Married Quarters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans the Government has to extend the period of time separating spouses of service personnel have to vacate his Department's accommodation.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","32655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487144","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-11","<p>In accordance with NATO guidelines on Defence expenditure, spending on the upkeep of the defence estate to support our Armed Forces does count towards the Government's pledge to spend at least two per cent of GDP on defence.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-04-11T15:21:35.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487144/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487144/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-24","Defence: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether spending on the upkeep of the defence estate counts towards the Government's pledge to spend at least two per cent of GDP on defence, as defined by NATO.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","32645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487145","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Ministry of Defence-Sponsored Cadet Forces comprise the Sea Cadet Corps, the Combined Cadet Force, the Army Cadet Force, and the Air Training Corps.</p><p>The Department has not formally assessed the potential contribution of its Cadet Forces in reducing the incidence of serious youth violence. However, the 131,000 Cadets involved follow a wide variety of well-organised, enjoyable and challenging military-themed activities in a safely-managed environment.</p><p>Experience shows that these activities allow Cadets to develop a sense of responsibility and service to the community, self-reliance, leadership, teamwork, communication skills and respect for authority and for others. In undertaking these activities, Cadets can gain nationally-recognised educational and vocational qualifications.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-04-11T16:14:54.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487145/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487145/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-24","Crimes of Violence: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the potential contribution of cadet forces to reducing the incidence of serious youth violence.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","32594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487146","Department for Education","false","2016-04-12","<p>The information requested is not held in the required format.</p><p>The Department’s register of educational establishments in England and Wales, EduBase, contains the postal address details of all schools including the postal town which may differ from the actual town where the school is located.</p><p>The EduBase system is publically available and can be accessed at: <a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/home.xhtml" target="_blank">http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/home.xhtml</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-04-12T11:19:38.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487146/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487146/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-24","Secondary Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, in how many towns there is no choice of secondary education provision.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","32593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487147","Department for Education","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Department for Education is working with the Home Office on a series of measures to reduce the incidence of serious youth violence.</p><p>In January 2016, the Home Office published its Ending Gang Violence and Exploitation approach. Among its priorities, this publication describes action to protect locations where vulnerable young people can be targeted, including pupil referral units and residential children’s care homes. New regulations and guidance, introduced in 2015, make it clear that homes can prevent a child leaving the home where there is an immediate risk to their safety – which would include where a gang was seeking to lure a child away for involvement in gang activities. The Department for Education has also undertaken a stock-take of frontline practice in relation to missing children, which will inform and help to shape ongoing work to strengthen and improve practice with the Association of Directors of Children’s Services.</p><p>The Ending Gang Violence and Exploitation publication also states that the Department for Education continues to focus on action to improve school attendance. Regular attendance plays a vital role in keeping young people away from gang involvement and other crime and antisocial behaviour. The Department has, from September 2015, reduced the threshold for ‘persistent absence’ from 15% to 10%, emphasising the message that attending school should be a priority for every pupil.</p><p>In March 2016, the Home Office published its Modern Crime Prevention Strategy, outlining measures to strengthen the Government’s response to knife crime. This publication notes that the Home Office is working with the Department for Education to deliver prevention messages in schools; teaching school pupils to recognise and challenge unhealthy and exploitative relationships, to prevent them from being abused or from engaging in abuse themselves. We are working with the Personal, Social, Health and Economic Education Association to train teaching staff in areas that seek help, to help them to teach young people to recognise and avoid exploitation and abuse.</p><p>The Modern Crime Prevention Strategy also highlights that the Department for Education will work with the Home Office on how best to raise awareness in school age children about the risks of carrying knives, and the role schools can play to build resilience in children and young people so they do not give in to peer pressure to carry knives.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-04-11T15:34:47.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487147/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487147/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-24","Crimes of Violence: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what contribution her Department is making to Government steps to reduce the incidence of serious youth violence.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","32651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487148","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-18","<p>Government policies supported investment of around £7.4bn on energy efficiency measures<sup>1</sup> over the last parliament.</p><p> </p><p>This included spending of:</p><p> </p><p>£2.9bn on ECO and the Green Deal<sup>2</sup></p><p>£3.8bn on CERT</p><p>£0.7bn on CESP<sup>3,4</sup></p><p> </p><p>During the course of this parliament, Government policies are expected to support investment of around £3.6bn. This includes spending of<sup>5</sup>:</p><p> </p><p>£1.7bn on ECO<sup>6</sup></p><p>£1.9bn on ECO’s successor<sup>7</sup></p><p>£0.1bn on the Green Deal<sup>8</sup></p><p> </p><p>The planned level of spend this parliament reflects Government’s desire to minimise the impact of energy efficiency policies on consumers’ energy bills, reduce reliance on subsidies, and set long-term policy frameworks. Government intends to focus investment on the households that need it most, with the aim of tackling the root causes of fuel poverty.</p><p> </p><p>We are working to deliver our schemes more efficiently by reducing administrative complexity. This will improve the overall value for money and ensure as much of the cost of the schemes as possible goes towards delivery.</p><p> </p><p>A reformed domestic supplier obligation (ECO) from April 2017 will upgrade the energy efficiency of over 200,000 homes per year for the 5 years to 2022, tackling the root cause of fuel poverty. Our extension of the Warm Home Discount to 2020/21 at current levels of £320m per annum will also help vulnerable households with their energy bills.</p><p> </p><p>Together through ECO and Warm Home Discount we will be spending nearly £1 billion a year helping with energy bills. We expect to increase our spending focused on fuel poverty from April 2017 and again in April 2018.</p><p> </p><p>We intend to focus our efforts through ECO and WHD more effectively on the fuel poor, and will be consulting on our future approach in the forthcoming months.</p><p> </p><p><em>Footnotes: </em></p><p><em>[1] Supporting costs by measure type are not available, so it is not possible to provide spend on insulation measures specifically. </em></p><p><em>[2] Source: Green Deal and ECO stats <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/household-energy-efficiency-national-statistics-headline-release-february-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/household-energy-efficiency-national-statistics-headline-release-february-2016</a> </em></p><p><em>[3] Please note that as CERT ran from April 2008 – December 2012, and CESP from Sept 2009 – December 2012, these include some spend prior to 2010. </em></p><p><em>[4] Source CERT Evaluation <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-the-carbon-emissions-reduction-target-and-community-energy-saving-programme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-the-carbon-emissions-reduction-target-and-community-energy-saving-programme</a> (figures adjusted for inflation)</em></p><p><em>[5] Figures may not add up to £3.6bn due to rounding. </em></p><p><em>[6] Estimated ECO spend (April 2015- March 2017), as reported Future of the energy supplier obligation IA <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/373650/ECO_IA_with_SoS_e-sigf_v2.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/373650/ECO_IA_with_SoS_e-sigf_v2.pdf</a>. Note that suppliers over delivered against their ECO 1 targets (January 2013- March 2015), so actual spend by suppliers may be lower than estimated in the IA. Figures are adjusted for inflation. </em></p><p><em>[7] Supplier spend consistent with the 2015 Spending Review announcement <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/479749/52229_Blue%5b_Book_PU1865_Web_Accessible.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/479749/52229_Blue[_Book_PU1865_Web_Accessible.pdf</a> (page 39). </em></p><p><em>[8] Based on estimated Green Deal plans, Green Communities, and Green Deal Home improvement Fund spending from May 2015 to April 2020. </em></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-18T15:26:53.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487148/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487148/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487148/answer/previousversion/54517","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-24","Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 15 March 2016 to Question 26458, how much investment in energy efficiency measures (a) was made during the last Parliament and (b) will be made during this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","32639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487149","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-13","<p>The Department annually publishes the Digest of United Kingdom Energy Statistics (DUKES). Appendix A of DUKES contains data on the calorific value of fuels:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/447648/ DUKES_2015_Annex_A.pdf.</p><p> </p><p>The gross calorific value of dry biomass fuels, (the DUKES values have been corrected for moisture content), vary between 10 gigajoules per tonne (GJ/t) for poultry litter and 24 GJ/t for meat and bone meal. A typical dry wood based fuel has an energy content close to 19 GJ/t. Treatments such as torrefaction or charcoal production increase the energy density of biomass derived materials. However these manufactured biomass fuels are not commonly used for heating in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>A tonne of coal can also vary in heat content, depending on the rank of the coal, but lies between 24 GJ/t for bituminous coal as used in the pulp, paper and printing industries and 34 GJ/t of fuel for anthracite used in households. Typical bituminous house coal has a gross heat content of 30 GJ/t.</p><p> </p><p>These values represent the maximum heat available from a fuel in a laboratory test. The useful heat provided by combustion of that fuel to the business or home will depend on the efficiency of the combustor in which it is burnt and the design of the energy distribution system. The combustor efficiency can range from an open fire which may provide 20% of the energy in the fuel as useful heat, to modern condensing wood pellet boilers with gross efficiencies around 90%.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-13T13:26:53.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487149/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487149/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-24","Biofuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether her Department holds data on the amount of heat a tonne of biomass gives off when burned compared to a tonne of coal; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","32625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487150","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>We will provide advice to the independent committee that will assess Saudi Arabian military activity in Yemen, drawing on a range of information as required. Our Embassy operations in Yemen are suspended and since March 2011 Foreign and Commonwealth Office Travel Advice has consistently advised against all travel to Yemen.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-11T13:04:15.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487150/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487150/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Yemen: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 21 March 2016 to Question 31488, how many British officials who have provided advice to Saudi Arabia's internal investigation into the breaking of international humanitarian law in Yemen have visited Yemen as part of this investigation; and where each of those officials was based.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","32640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487151","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>We remain focused on steps which will secure progress towards a two-state solution. We continue to believe that the best way to achieve this is through negotiations. We are in close consultation with international partners about what kind of renewed process might lead to progress.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-11T14:39:21.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487151/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487151/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Middle East: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the prospects for the Middle East peace process.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","32661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487152","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The UN reports that between 26 March 2015 and 17 March 2016 there have been just under 9,000 casualties in Yemen including 3,218 civilians killed and a further 5,778 injured. The UK Government uses UN reports as one of its primary data sources.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-04-11T14:30:13.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487152/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487152/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information he holds on the number of civilians (a) killed and (b) injured in the Yemen conflict to date.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","32643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487153","Department of Health","false","2016-04-11","<p>The attached table shows the total general practitioner (GP) headcount and headcount per head of population in Enfield and London between 2010-14.</p><p>Information on the availability of GP appointments in Enfield North is not collected centrally.</p><p>We have invested in the Prime Minister’s GP Access Fund to test improved and innovative access to GP services. Across the two waves of the Fund, there are 57 schemes covering over 2,500 practices and over 18 million patients have benefited from improved access and transformational change at a local level. A wide variety of approaches are being tested through the Access Fund, including: evening and weekend appointments and better use of telecare and health apps; more innovative ways to access services by video call, email or telephone; and developing more integrated services with a single point of contact to co-ordinate patient services.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","32652","2016-04-11T13:45:21.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487153/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487153/answer","PQ32652 PQ32654 GP headcount 2010-14.xlsx","PQ32652 PQ32654 GP headcount 2010-14.xlsx","GP headcount 2010-14","GP headcount 2010-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487153/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-24","General Practitioners: Enfield North","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many GP appointments were available in Enfield North constituency in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","32654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487154","Department of Health","false","2016-04-11","<p>It is the responsibility of the professional regulators to set the standards and outcomes for education and training and approve training curricula to ensure newly qualified healthcare professionals are equipped with the knowledge, skills and attitudes to provide high quality patient care. It is the responsibility of employers to ensure staff receive appropriate training to deliver high quality healthcare. This includes training in suicide prevention. There are no plans to make it compulsory.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-04-11T14:56:28.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487154/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487154/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-24","Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government is taking to ensure all frontline NHS staff are trained in suicide prevention; and whether such training will be compulsory.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","32656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487155","Department of Health","false","2016-04-11","<p>The attached table shows the total general practitioner (GP) headcount and headcount per head of population in Enfield and London between 2010-14.</p><p>Information on the availability of GP appointments in Enfield North is not collected centrally.</p><p>We have invested in the Prime Minister’s GP Access Fund to test improved and innovative access to GP services. Across the two waves of the Fund, there are 57 schemes covering over 2,500 practices and over 18 million patients have benefited from improved access and transformational change at a local level. A wide variety of approaches are being tested through the Access Fund, including: evening and weekend appointments and better use of telecare and health apps; more innovative ways to access services by video call, email or telephone; and developing more integrated services with a single point of contact to co-ordinate patient services.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","32654","2016-04-11T13:45:21.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487155/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487155/answer","PQ32652 PQ32654 GP headcount 2010-14.xlsx","PQ32652 PQ32654 GP headcount 2010-14.xlsx","GP headcount 2010-14","GP headcount 2010-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487155/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-24","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many GPs were working in (a) Enfield North constituency, (b) Enfield and (c) London (i) in total and (ii) per head of population in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","32652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487156","Department of Health","false","2016-04-12","<p>Officials from Public Health England will be attending the conference and feeding back to Ministers on the issues discussed.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-04-12T13:14:48.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487156/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487156/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-24","AIDS: Conferences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which (a) ministers and (b) officials of his Department will be present at the International Aids Conference in Durban in July 2016.","false","Biography information for Mike Freer","Finchley and Golders Green","Mike Freer","32616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487157","Department of Health","false","2016-04-14","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are responsible for commissioning non-specialised mental health services to meet the needs of their local communities. NHS England has made the requirement of CCGs through the planning guidance document, <em>Delivering the Forward View: NHS Planning Guidance 2016/17 to 2020/21 (December 2015), </em>that they should increase their spending on mental health each year at least in line with the growth in their overall funding allocation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-14T15:28:23.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487157/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487157/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-24","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to reduce variations in mental health spending and services between clinical commissioning groups.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","32626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487158","Department of Health","false","2016-04-11","<p>Public Health England (PHE) has worked with the Faculty of Public Health (FPH), Royal Society for Public Health and Royal College of Psychiatrists in developing and implementing the public mental health leadership and workforce development framework. More recently the Royal College of Nursing, Chartered Institute for Environmental Health (CIEH), Association of Directors of Public Health (ADPH) and Institute for Health Visitors have endorsed the framework and signed up to its Call to Action. Mental health has been made a presidential priority for the FPH, CIEH and ADPH. PHE has provided information and guidance to inform the recent FPH curricula review, the Public Health Skills and Knowledge Framework review and the new Mental Health Skills and Knowledge Framework. PHE has also presented the framework to the United Kingdom People in Public Health Board, Skills for Care Mental Health Board, Health Education England Mental Health Advisory Board and the forthcoming Health Education England Public Health Advisory Board.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-04-11T14:59:29.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487158/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487158/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-24","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to implement recommendation 8 in the executive summary of Public Health England's March 2015 report entitled, Public mental health leadership and workforce development framework, on working with relevant colleges, faculties and boards overseeing professional training to include mental health within public health curricula.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","32630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487159","Department of Health","false","2016-04-14","<p>The requested information is not collected.</p><p>NHS England advises that general practitioners (GPs) are funded per head of population to deliver GP medical services. The Southampton Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) will be commissioning primary care on behalf of NHS England from 1 April 2016 and NHS England confirms across the CCG’s forecast population this funding is £124 per head of population.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-14T15:23:33.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487159/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487159/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-24","General Practitioners: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average cost is per patient attending a GP's surgery in Southampton.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","32592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487160","Department of Health","false","2016-04-11","<p>Public Health England (PHE) has been collating practice examples of mental health promotion training available for frontline public health practitioners. Information will help inform the commissioning of training locally. PHE is working with the Royal Society for Public Health and other partners to identify gaps in mental health promotion training provision and opportunities to fill these gaps, such as developing e-learning training modules.</p><p> </p><p>At a local level, PHE centres are working with Health Education England (HEE) colleagues to identify and co-ordinate provision of training to practitioners and identify needs and training opportunities.</p><p> </p><p>PHE contributed to the Mental Health Task Force report and has integrated the priority of increasing the training within the Taskforce’s recommendations. Work will be led by HEE, supported by PHE.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-11T13:50:30.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487160/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487160/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-24","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to implement recommendation 12 in the executive summary of Public Health England's March 2015 report entitled, Public mental health leadership and workforce development framework, on supporting increased access to a range of mental health promotion training for frontline public health practitioners.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","32629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487161","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Home Office do not hold data that allows us to establish how many women with mental health issues in the UK have been trafficked.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-11T13:32:02.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487161/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487161/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-24","Human Trafficking: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will estimate how many and what proportion of all women with mental health issues in the UK have been internally or internationally trafficked.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","32631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487162","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-15","<p>The Secretary of State has published an explanatory note setting out the method of calculation of the Transition Grant. Copies have been made available in the libraries of both Houses. It is available to view at:<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/510870/Explanatory_note_on_the_allocation_of_the_Transition_Grant.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/510870/Explanatory_note_on_the_allocation_of_the_Transition_Grant.pdf</a>.</p><p>Individual authority allocations were published on 8 February as part of the Core Spending Power: Supporting Information tables: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/corespending-power-final-local-government-finance-settlement-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/corespending-power-final-local-government-finance-settlement-2016-to-2017</a>.</p><p>The Secretary of State has already addressed questions from the House on this matter. I refer the hon. Member to the debate on Local Government Finance Report (England) on 10 February, <em>Official Report, </em>Columns 1643-1645.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-04-15T14:58:51.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487162/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487162/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-24","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the final local government finance settlement 2016-17, published on 8 February 2016, if he will place a copy of the (a) methodology used for calculating the distribution  and (b) detailed model used to calculate the allocation to each individual authority of the 2016-17 transitional grant in the Library; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","32596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487163","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>Recorded crime figures for the period 2010 to 2014 do not directly map on to the two categories in the question. Data on human trafficking for sexual exploitation shows that one case of this type was recorded by Humberside in 2012/13. Crime recording rules stipulate that only the most serious offence in a sequence of crimes is recorded, so it is possible that other cases of trafficking for sexual exploitation offences have been recorded under even more serious crime types.</p><p>On a principal offence basis, no defendants were proceeded against, convicted or sentenced at magistrates’ courts during the period 2010 to 2014 for offences related to human trafficking and forced labour in the Humberside Police Force Area. Such data is recorded on the basis of the location of the magistrates’ court where proceedings started, so it may be that an offence recorded in Humberside was then proceeded against in another police force area.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-11T13:53:09.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487163/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487163/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-24","Slavery: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many cases of (a) human trafficking and (b) forced labour have been recorded by Humberside Police for each year from 2010 to 2014; in how many such cases prosecutions were brought; and what the outcomes were of those prosecutions.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","32595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487164","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>There are on-going criminal investigations and prosecutions into matters connected with cheating in ETS tests and it would be inappropriate to release any information or details of correspondence in the circumstances.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-11T12:28:18.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487164/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487164/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-24","Educational Testing Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish all correspondence between her Department and ETS relating to allegations of English language text fraud.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","32637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487165","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The investigation into the abuse of English language testing in 2014 revealed extremely serious, large scale, organised fraud and it is right that the Home Office took decisive action in respect of those against whom there was evidence of cheating. We are disappointed by the decision of the Upper Tribunal and, once we have the full determination, we will consider our next steps carefully, including an appeal of this decision.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-11T16:12:48.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487165/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487165/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-24","Educational Testing Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will commission an independent inquiry into the role of (a) her Department and (b) ETS related to allegations of English Language Test fraud.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","32636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487166","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>We are disappointed by the decision of the recent Upper Tribunal. Once we have the full determination we will carefully consider next steps, including appealing the decision.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-11T12:26:26.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487166/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487166/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-24","Educational Testing Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what independent scrutiny her Department commissioned of reports of invalid and questionable results in English Language tests conducted by ETS.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","32659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487167","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-11","<p>Conflict is making humanitarian access within Yemen extremely difficult. Humanitarian agencies report that they are constrained in reaching areas of greatest humanitarian need and delivering assistance for a number of reasons including bureaucratic requirements imposed by the authorities, access challenges for international staff, insecurity in a number of districts, and a proliferation of checkpoints across the country.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to urge all parties to the conflict to take all reasonable steps to facilitate rapid, safe and unhindered humanitarian access. We work with trusted and impartial partners such as UN agencies and NGOs who have good access and a strong track record of delivering and monitoring assistance in difficult and dangerous places.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-11T12:16:50.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487167/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487167/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-24","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of barriers to humanitarian agencies reaching people in need in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","32642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487168","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-11","<p>As set out in the aid strategy, UK aid: tackling global challenges in the national interest, the government will ensure that every penny of money spent delivers value for taxpayers, and projects that do not will be cancelled. Departments follow good financial management principles set out in HM Treasury guidance in ‘Managing Public Money’ for all their expenditure. In addition, ODA spend is subject to scrutiny by the Independent Commission for Aid Impact. The UK Aid Strategy also commits all departments to achieving greater levels of transparency in aid spend.</p><p> </p><p>DFID has robust internal processes such as strong ministerial oversight, mandatory reviews on all programmes, detailed management information for use at all levels of the organisation including on project performance and quality. Other departments will have their own arrangements and DFID will continue to share good practice advice with them.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-11T12:11:50.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487168/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487168/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-24","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking ensure that UK overseas aid is spent effectively and transparently.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","32665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487169","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-11","<p>The UK government will be represented at the International AIDS Conference in Durban in July 2016. Precise attendance has still to be finalised.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-11T15:52:59.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487169/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487169/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-24","AIDS: Conferences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which (a) ministers and (b) officials of her Department will be present at the International Aids Conference in Durban in July 2016.","false","Biography information for Mike Freer","Finchley and Golders Green","Mike Freer","32615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487170","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-11","<p>We continue to play an active role in cross-Government work to tackle gangs and prevent youth violence.</p><p> </p><p>Youth reoffending is too high which is why the justice Secretary has asked Charlie Taylor to conduct a review of youth justice. He will report back later this year with recommendations.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-11T16:43:34.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487170/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487170/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-24","Crimes of Violence: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what contribution his Department is making to Government steps to reduce the incidence of serious youth violence.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","32649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487171","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>This information is published on Network Rail’s website - <a href="http://www.networkrail.co.uk/transparency/datasets/" target="_blank">http://www.networkrail.co.uk/transparency/datasets/</a> - covering the years 2012-13 to 2014-15. 2015-16 is not yet available.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-11T15:40:09.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487171/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487171/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-24","Southern: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much Network Rail has paid to Southern Rail in compensation for late running and skipped stopping in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","32653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487172","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Department holds the information as set out in the table attached. Not all operators are required to provide such figures.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-11T15:46:03.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487172/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487172/answer","032660 - TOC compensation 2010-15.pdf","032660 - TOC compensation 2010-15.pdf","32660 - TOC compensation 2010-2015","32660 - TOC compensation 2010-2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487172/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-24","Railways: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much Southern Rail/GTR has paid in compensation payments to passengers in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","32660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487173","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Airports Commission undertook a range of detailed assessments to support its Final Report published in July 2015. The analysis included a detailed assessment of transport network impacts for each of the Commission’s three short-listed options.</p><p> </p><p>Copies of the Commission’s <em>Surface Access: Dynamic Modelling Report</em> its <em>Local and Strategic Roads Modelling Study</em> for the Heathrow Airport North West Runway Proposals, and the <em>Commission’s Freight Impact Study</em> were published alongside its Final Report, and are available from the Commission website at the following links:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/437460/surface-access-dynamic-modelling-report-heathrow-airport-north-west-runway.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/437460/surface-access-dynamic-modelling-report-heathrow-airport-north-west-runway.pdf</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/437459/surface-access-local-and-strategic-roads-modelling-study-heathrow-airport-north-west-runway.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/437459/surface-access-local-and-strategic-roads-modelling-study-heathrow-airport-north-west-runway.pdf</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/437276/surface-access-freight-impacts-study.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/437276/surface-access-freight-impacts-study.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government will carefully consider all the evidence set out when making a decision on the location of additional runway capacity.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T15:10:53.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487173/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487173/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-24","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an assessment of the effect on traffic congestion in (a) Brentford and Isleworth constituency and (b) the London borough of Hounslow of the proposed third runway at Heathrow.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","32635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487174","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-12","<p>Under the Convention on International Civil Aviation the responsibility for establishing minimum rest periods for airline pilots rests with the state in which an airline is based. The EU cannot therefore impose requirements for rest periods on non EU airlines. Minimum rest periods for the crew of EU airlines are already established by Commission Regulation 83/2014.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-12T14:24:54.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487174/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487174/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-24","Aviation: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will discuss with the European Aviation Safety Agency agreeing a minimum numbers of hours for airline pilots between each flight for EU and non-EU carriers entering EU airspace.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","32623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487175","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Department does not collect data on how many emergency landings there have been at Heathrow Airport. However if serious enough, such incidents would be counted amongst data for safety related events. These are defined as an event which endanger or which, if not corrected or addressed, could endanger an aircraft, its occupants or any other person. They have to be reported to the Civil Aviation Authority as part of the Mandatory Occurrence Reporting Scheme (MORS).</p><p> </p><p>Occurrence reporting is now covered by (EU) Regulation No 376/2014. The Regulation requires that the reporting, analysis and follow-up to such occurrences remain confidential. However, the Regulation does permit information to be released on request to interested parties that have a genuine safety related need for the information. An application can be made at <a href="http://www.caa.co.uk" target="_blank">www.caa.co.uk</a>.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T13:47:46.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487175/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487175/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-24","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many emergency landings there have been at Heathrow Airport in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","32633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487176","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Elizabeth line will replace the existing two train per hour Heathrow Connect service from May 2018 providing a 4 train per hour service to Terminals 1 to 4, operating alongside the existing 4 train per hour Heathrow Express service. This will offer significant improvements in connectivity from and to Heathrow, particularly from the West End, the City and Canary Wharf.</p><p> </p><p>Heathrow is also served by regular Piccadilly line services from central London. Upgrading this line is a matter for the Mayor and Transport for London who plan to introduce new modern signalling systems and new trains to provide 60% more capacity (the equivalent of up to 21,000 customers per hour).</p><p> </p><p>For any improvements associated with airport expansion, the Government will agree the nature and scale of the surface access transport as part of its decision on its preferred scheme for additional airport capacity in the South East. The Government has also been clear that it expects the scheme promoter to meet the costs of any surface access proposals that are required as a direct result of airport expansion and from which they will directly benefit.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T14:06:40.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487176/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487176/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-24","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has to increase capacity on public transport links to Heathrow Airport from central London.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","32634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487177","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>Ministers consider all of their statutory duties in considering new policies and impact assessments are published as is appropriate. A number of impact assessments have been published during the passage of the recent Welfare Reform Act. These use the whole population as a base but do not focus specifically on DWP employees.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-11T16:11:46.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487177/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/487177/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-24","Welfare State: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to his oral contribution of 21 March 2016, Official Report, column 1284, whether an impact assessment has been carried out on the effect of social security reform on employees in his Department.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","32638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508949","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Government has protected overall police spending for the coming Spending Review period, once police precept is taken into account. The public can be confident that over the next four years the police will have the resources they need to carry on cutting crime, fighting terrorism and keeping the people of this country safe.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-11T15:57:20.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508949/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508949/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-24","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of police funding after service reorganisation.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","904394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508951","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>This Government is committed to stamping out Modern Slavery, including human trafficking. Our Modern slavery Act gives law enforcement agencies the tools they need to tackle this heinous crime, places a duty on large businesses to report on their steps to prevent modern slavery in their global supply chains, and ensures that perpetrators can receive suitably severe sentences of up to life imprisonment.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-04-11T15:56:06.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508951/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508951/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-24","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to tackle people trafficking.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","904392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508952","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>Decisions about the number of officers deployed to neighbourhood policing, and their specific roles, are for Chief Constables and democratically accountable Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs). They are responsible for ensuring the needs of the local community are met. Priorities for each area are set out in the PCC’s – in London the Mayor’s - Police and Crime Plan. Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary independently assesses the efficiency and effectiveness of police force activity, including neighbourhood policing.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-11T15:55:45.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508952/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508952/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-24","Community Policing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the adequacy of neighbourhood policing capacity.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","904391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508953","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The United Kingdom’s border controls are among the toughest in the world. Border Force works closely with other law enforcement agencies, including the National Crime Agency and Police, to combat suspected human trafficking and to target and disrupt those who would attempt to smuggle prohibited and restricted goods such as firearms and illegal drugs in to the UK.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-04-11T15:57:51.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508953/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/508953/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-24","Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to (a) stop firearms, drugs and other contraband from entering the UK and (b) tackle human trafficking in UK waters.","false","Biography information for Suella Braverman","Fareham","Suella Fernandes","904396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510067","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>The Government remains committed to the success of the deal. The IAEA’s 26 February report on Iran’s nuclear activities concluded that Iran was complying with the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPoA). We have been working to help businesses take advantage of new commercial opportunities and to ensure that Iran benefits from sanctions relief.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-12T15:45:20.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510067/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510067/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress has been made on implementation of the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action with Iran.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","904418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510395","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>The UK is committed to peace talks between the Syrian parties, under UN auspices in Geneva and continues to work closely with the International Syria Support Group. The UK encouraged the UN Special Envoy for Syria and the Syrian opposition to include women in the negotiations. The UN established a Women’s Advisory Board and the opposition’s negotiating team includes women.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","904412","2016-04-12T15:40:12.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510395/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510395/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to support efforts to bring an end to the conflict in Syria.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh","904416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510396","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>The release of political prisoners has been an early priority for the new NLD-led government, with over 100 having been released since Friday.</p><p>The UK Government has long campaigned on the issue of political prisoners in Burma and we welcome this quick action.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-04-12T15:53:21.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510396/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510396/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Burma: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Burmese counterpart on prisoners of conscience in that country.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","904420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510397","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","We are committed to strengthening our Commonwealth engagement and ties with Commonwealth allies. We continue to engage with organisations like the Commonwealth Enterprise and Investment Council to boost trade and increase prosperity within the Commonwealth. As part of these efforts, the UK and Malta will be co-hosting the first Commonwealth Trade Ministers meeting in March 2017.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-04-12T15:43:05.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510397/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510397/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to promote trade and diplomatic connections between the UK and other Commonwealth countries.","false","Biography information for Mary Robinson","Cheadle","Mary Robinson","904411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510398","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>We remain concerned about Israel’s extensive use of administrative detention which, according to international law, should be used only when security makes this absolutely necessary. Officials regularly raise concerns about the treatment of administrative detainees with their Israeli counterparts.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-12T15:43:05.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510398/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510398/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Israel: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Israeli counterpart on the use of administrative detention in that country.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","904414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510399","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>The Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p><p>The Chancellor, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Tatton, has announced that the Treasury will publish a comprehensive analysis of the long-term economic costs and benefits of EU membership and the risks associated with an exit.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-04-12T15:31:08.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510399/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510399/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with HM Treasury on the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the economy.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","904417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510400","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>The relationship between Afghanistan and Pakistan is crucial for the security and prosperity of both countries. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runneymede and Weybridge, visited Afghanistan and Pakistan last month and urged their leaders to work closely together, including on the reconciliation process.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-12T15:44:02.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510400/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510400/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Afghanistan: Pakistan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to encourage greater diplomatic co-operation between Afghanistan and Pakistan.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","904419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510401","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>In January I visited Juba and held meetings with President Salva Kiir, members of the opposition and civil society. In the margins of the African Union Summit I met with the Leader of the Opposition Riek Machar. In all those meetings I emphasised the importance of forming the transitional government without delay. The UK has also worked closely with key countries in the region and in the UN Security Council to build pressure on the parties to form a government of national unity.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-04-12T16:10:28.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510401/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510401/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","South Sudan: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he has taken to support the formation of the transitional government of national unity in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","904415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510402","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>Our relationship with China is strong and prosperous. We are building on the global partnership established during last year’s Chinese State Visit, by cooperating on international challenges and boosting trade and investment. We also have frank discussions on difficult issues including steel over-capacity, human rights and the South China Sea.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-04-12T15:44:51.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510402/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510402/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","China: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the strength of diplomatic and economic relations between China and the UK.","false","Biography information for Alan Mak","Havant","Mr Alan Mak","904413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510403","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>The UK is committed to peace talks between the Syrian parties, under UN auspices in Geneva and continues to work closely with the International Syria Support Group. The UK encouraged the UN Special Envoy for Syria and the Syrian opposition to include women in the negotiations. The UN established a Women’s Advisory Board and the opposition’s negotiating team includes women.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","904416","2016-04-12T15:40:12.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510403/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510403/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Syria: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to promote the participation of women in the Syrian peace negotiations.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","904412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510404","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>Sri Lanka has made encouraging progress towards fulfilling its commitments to UNHRC Resolution 30/1 but we recognise there remains much to be done. We look forward to the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights’ assessment of progress at the next Human Rights Council in June.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-04-12T16:00:39.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510404/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510404/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-24","Sri Lanka: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress has  been made on implementation of the UN Human Rights Council Resolution 30/1 on Sri Lanka.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","904421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511663","Wales Office","false","2016-04-13","<p>Last month’s Budget demonstrated the scale of this Government’s ambition for Wales, delivering a historic City Deal for Cardiff and a commitment to Swansea Bay, cutting tax for 1.4 million Welsh men and women, as well as opening the door for a growth deal for North Wales.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-04-13T14:13:32.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511663/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511663/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-03-24","Budget March 2016: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on Wales of measures announced in the Budget 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","904368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511664","Wales Office","false","2016-04-13","<p>The Children’s Commissioner for Wales plays an essential role as part of wider efforts to protect children.</p><p> </p><p>I have already spoken to the Commissioner by phone and look forward to further engagement in the future to discuss any concerns she may have about the extent of her remit.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-04-13T14:16:30.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511664/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511664/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-03-24","Children's Commissioner for Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether he has had discussions with the Welsh Government on strengthening and extending the remit of the Children's Commissioner for Wales.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","904369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511665","Wales Office","false","2016-04-13","<p>In order to become truly accountable to the people of Wales it is vital that the Welsh Government takes more responsibility for raising, through taxation, the money that it spends.</p><p> </p><p>We will, as part of the Wales Bill, remove the requirement for a referendum before the devolution of powers to vary the rates of income tax in Wales.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-04-13T13:56:47.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511665/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511665/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-03-24","Welsh Government: Accountability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment he has made of the financial accountability of government in Wales.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","904374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511666","Wales Office","false","2016-04-13","<p>Universal Credit is transforming the lives of the most disadvantaged children and families in this country.</p><p>This Government recognises that work is the best route out of poverty.</p><p>Our welfare reforms have resulted in record numbers of Welsh people going out to work – strengthening families through financial security and improving the life chances of children throughout Wales.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-04-13T14:10:50.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511666/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511666/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-03-24","Universal Credit: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment he has made of the effect of recent changes to universal credit on families in Wales.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","904367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511667","Wales Office","false","2016-04-13","<p>I have received no recent representations.</p><p>All areas that met the strict criteria around pump price, population density and the cost of fuel transportation were included in the extension to the rural fuel rebate scheme introduced in April 2015.</p><p>There are currently no plans to extend the scheme beyond the qualifying areas.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-04-13T14:18:06.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511667/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511667/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-03-24","Fuels: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what representations he has received from the Welsh Government on the fuel duty rebate scheme.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","904371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484822","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-05","<p>The UK coordinates with other EU member states to promote the universality of the Rome Statute. We offer support to any State that is in the process of ratifying the Rome Statute or needs assistance in adopting the national legislation needed to enact the full implementation of the statute.</p><p>Whether Iraq chooses to accede to the Rome Statute is a matter for the Government of Iraq.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-05T13:10:45.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484822/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484822/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-23","Iraq: International Criminal Court","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Iraq about Iraq becoming a signatory to the Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Leeds",,"The Lord Bishop of Leeds","HL7331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484824","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-05","<p>This Government wants to see accountability for Daesh abuses, and has supported efforts to document them. The UK co-sponsored the UN Human Rights Council Resolution in September 2014 mandating the investigation of Daesh abuses.</p><p>In Iraq, we are funding training for human rights defenders to improve victim support and case documentation of sexual violence committed by Daesh. It is hoped that this evidence will be able to be used in the future to hold the perpetrators to account.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-05T13:10:59.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484824/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484824/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-23","Iraq: Islamic State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to record the atrocities that have been committed by Daesh in Iraq so that, in due course, offenders may be brought to justice.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Leeds",,"The Lord Bishop of Leeds","HL7332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484825","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-05","<p>There are credible reports that Daesh has used chemical weapons in Iraq. The Government of Iraq, with support from the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW), investigated allegations of chemical weapons use in Iraq last year and has concluded that sulphur mustard was used against Peshmerga fighters on 11 August 2015.</p><p>Allegations that Daesh attacked the village of Taza on 8 March 2016, possibly with sulphur mustard, are being investigated by the Government of Iraq, along with two other recent allegations of Daesh use of chemical weapons. Such behaviour would be consistent with Daesh’s record of complete disregard for human rights and international norms and values. We welcome the OPCW Director General’s press statement of 23 March offering assistance to the Government of Iraq.</p><p>We continue to monitor all allegations of chemical weapon use very closely, and condemn all such attacks by anyone, anywhere.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-05T13:11:14.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484825/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484825/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-23","Iraq: Islamic State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of reports of the use of chemical weapons by Daesh in Iraq.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Leeds",,"The Lord Bishop of Leeds","HL7333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484826","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-05","<p>The Government is committed to delivering a permanent, fit-for-purpose Consulate General platform in Erbil at the earliest opportunity.</p><p>Significant changes to the security situation in Iraq have necessitated that we review our requirements and plans for the Consulate General platform in order to ensure that we are able to meet our political, security, prosperity and humanitarian objectives, both now and in the future. We continue to offer an uninterrupted service from our current Consulate General platform and continue to explore options for the acquisition of appropriate office accommodation for the future.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-05T13:11:27.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484826/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484826/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-23","Iraq: Kurds","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to establishing new consular premises in Iraqi Kurdistan.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Leeds",,"The Lord Bishop of Leeds","HL7334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484827","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-05","<p>We regularly raise the importance of securing a new budget agreement between Baghdad and Erbil with senior representatives of the Government of Iraq and the Kurdistan Regional Government (KRG).</p><p>During his visit to Iraq in March the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), raised the issue with both Iraqi Prime Minister Haider al-Abadi, and President of the Kurdistan Region, Masoud Barzani.</p><p>The Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Ellwood), underlined the importance of a new agreement with Iraqi Foreign Minister Ibrahim al-Jaafari and KRG Deputy Prime Minister Qubad Talabani in Iraq in December 2015.</p><p>Officials at our Embassy in Baghdad and our Consulate General in Erbil continue to highlight the benefits of a united Iraq and the benefits to both sides of agreeing a new oil sharing and budget arrangement.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-05T13:11:46.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484827/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484827/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-23","Iraq: Kurds","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Iraq on resolving the budget impasse with the Kurdish Regional Government.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Leeds",,"The Lord Bishop of Leeds","HL7335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484828","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-08","The case for legislation including criminal powers is currently being reviewed by the Department.<p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-04-08T11:59:50.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484828/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484828/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-23","Sports: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of Germany's Anti-Doping Law passed on 13 November 2015 and what plans they have either to use the Fraud Act 2006, or to introduce primary legislation, to enable the prosecution of those who conduct sports fraud through the use of banned performance-enhancing drugs.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484829","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","true","2016-04-08","<p>The UKAD budget (income and DCMS funding) was £7.2 million in 2011/12; £7.7 million in 2012/13; £7.5 million on 2013/14; and £7.5 million in 2014/15. The 2015/16 total budget is subject to finalised accounts. Its workforce is recruited based on each individual's particular set of skills to help deliver the anti-doping programme effectively. UKAD's role as secretariat to the Pre-Rio Anti-Doping Taskforce is through an agreement with the World Anti-Doping Agency. An additional full-time member of staff has been secured to carry out the task-force work so resources will not be diverted from UK Anti-Doping’s core programmes. As the honourable member will know, shocking allegations of doping in British sport emerged over the weekend, and UKAD's role in investigating the matter. The Secretary of State for DCMS has ordered an urgent independent investigation into what action was taken when these allegations were first received and what more needs to be done to ensure that British sport remains clean. We intend to keep both houses fully informed of developments.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-04-08T13:41:52.643Z","2016-04-15T11:30:55.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484829/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484829/answer",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484829/answer/previousversion/54178",,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-23","UK Anti-doping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the budget for UK Anti-Doping for each of the last five years; how many specialists it employs; what contractual relationship it has with the International Olympic Committee and the World Anti-Doping Agency to act as a secretariat for the International Olympic Committee Pre-Rio Anti-Doping Taskforce; and what assessment they have made of whether UK Anti-Doping has the resources necessary to fulfil its role effectively.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484830","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-08","<p>Sir Craig Reedie was appointed a Special Advisor to UK Anti-Doping in 2009. The role was created to provide expert advice to UK Anti-Doping, primarily during its formative phase, as and when required. Under this appointment, Sir Craig Reedie was not commissioned to provide any expert advice and therefore received no payment from UK Anti-Doping. He formally stood down from this role on his appointment to President of the World Anti-Doping Agency in 2014.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-04-08T13:58:37.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484830/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484830/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-23","UK Anti-doping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government between which dates the current President of the World Anti-Doping Agency was a consultant to UK Anti-Doping; how much he was paid; and what his responsibilities were.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484831","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-08","<p>Her Majesty's Government is satisfied that it has a clear understanding of the constraints on legislation imposed by the Consumer Rights Directive and has not to date sought discussions with the European Commission on this matter.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-04-08T11:22:16.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484831/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484831/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-23","Tickets: Sales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made in discussions with the European Commission about whether it would be in accordance with the EU Consumer Rights Directive for both primary and secondary market ticket sellers to be required to provide a unique reference number to ensure event organisers can track ticket sales.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484833","Home Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>The City of London Police is working closely with the Society of Ticketing Agents and Retailers and is actively part of a number of initiatives they are taking to raise standards within the ticketing industry. They are also engaging directly with organisers of major ticketing events in an attempt to stop ticketing touts obtaining tickets on a large scale and proactively search for new websites set up to sell tickets which are in high demand. The City of London Police is also actively engaged with the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills in their review of secondary ticketing platforms.</p><p>All ticketing fraud reports received through Action Fraud, where viable lines of enquiry can be identified and links between cases can be seen, are disseminated by the National Fraud Intelligence Bureau to the local police force for investigation.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-04-12T14:34:38.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484833/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484833/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-23","Tickets: Touting","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 9 July 2015 (HL Deb, col 243), what action the City of London Police and Action Fraud have taken to enforce the ticket touting controls set out in the Consumer Rights Act 2015; and what action is being taken in cases where the law is being broken.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484834","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-08","<p>Government and its Arm's Length Bodies have helped deliver a strong sporting legacy from London 2012, including 1.65 million more people playing sport regularly than when London won the bid for the Games back in 2005; over £1 billion over 4 years invested in youth and community sport; £150 million a year for primary school sport in the 2013-14 academic year and the following two years; and a 13% increase in funding for elite sport for the four years leading to Rio 2016.</p><p>The Olympic and Paralympic Legacy Cabinet Committee met during the last parliament and was not reconstituted in this parliament. Its membership covered a wide variety of government departments, reflecting the breadth of the government and Mayor of London's legacy plans. The responsibilities and the budget of the Olympic and Paralympic Legacy Unit now fall within the DCMS sport team.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-04-08T13:43:22.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484834/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484834/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-23","Olympic Games 2012","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the Cabinet Office Olympic and Paralympic Legacy Cabinet Committee last met; what is its membership; what is the budget of the Olympic and Paralympic Legacy Unit; and what has been the tangible output of its work in delivering a sports legacy from the London Olympic and Paralympic Games since 2012.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484835","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-01","<p>European Regulation No 648/2012 (EMIR) establishes a strict supervisory framework for CCPs, which in the UK are regulated by the Bank of England.</p><p> </p><p>EMIR’s requirements – which continue to apply in the event of a merger or change of control of a CCP – include that a CCP must be sufficiently well-resourced to withstand extreme market events, including the simultaneous default of its two largest clearing members.</p><p> </p><p>In the event of a qualifying change of control the Bank of England must under EMIR also assess the suitability of the proposed acquirer and financial soundness of the proposed acquisition.</p><p> </p><p>Copies of the Bank of England’s 2016 report on supervision of financial market infrastructures were laid before Parliament on 4 March and are available in the House library.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL7153","2016-04-01T12:29:45.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484835/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484835/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-23","Financial Markets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have agreed to cross-margining of variable payments through LCH Clearnet and Eurex; and if so, who will be responsible for regulating these separate entities; and whether they have required any increase in capital or margin.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL7342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484836","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-05","<p>Sugar production is not directly subsidised in the UK. However, sugar beet growers in the UK are entitled to make a claim for support under the Basic Payment Scheme of the Common Agricultural Policy.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-04-05T09:48:36.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484836/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484836/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-23","Sugar: Subsidies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much the UK contributes towards the subsidisation of sugar production.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL7343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484837","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-01","<p>We have enormous admiration and respect for the unique contribution and sacrifice made by bomber aircrew who served outside of the UK. Sir John Holmes, in his Military Medals Review, specifically included a reconsideration of recognition for Bomber Command, although he recommended not to award medallic recognition to those who flew from outside the UK. This decision was made independently of the Ministry of Defence and subsequently agreed by the Committee on the Grant of Honours, Decorations and Medals and Her Majesty The Queen.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-04-01T13:26:53.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484837/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484837/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-23","Military Decorations: World War II","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why the Bomber Command clasp is not awarded to veterans who served with 205 Group and flew sorties over occupied Europe from Southern Italy, and what recent consideration they have given to this issue.","false","Biography information for Lord Beith",,"Lord Beith","HL7344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484838","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-06","<p>The Court of Protection deals with some of the most vulnerable people in our society and is responsible for making difficult decisions including where a person must be deprived of their liberty for the purpose of care or treatment. The protection of vulnerable people is a priority for the Government and we remain committed to finding a fair and proportionate resolution. We are considering whether changes need to be made to the way these cases are dealt with in the courts following the recent ruling on this topic.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-04-06T15:55:15.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484838/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484838/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-23","Court of Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that cases in the Court of Protection involving personal liberty are not delayed by lack of representation for persons with mental disabilities, following the recent ruling of that Court requiring representation in such cases.","false","Biography information for Lord Beith",,"Lord Beith","HL7345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484839","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-04","<p>We are committed to protecting our country from tree pests and diseases and we want to ensure that the ash tree continues to have a place in our environment. To support this we have invested over £21 million in tree health research.</p><p> </p><p>Natural tolerance to ash dieback does exist and the UK is leading research to identify resistant strains. Ash trees have a wide genetic diversity and potential for greater levels of resistance compared to other tree species affected by diseases.</p><p> </p><p>There have been no findings of emerald ash borer anywhere in the EU. We have identified this pest as a threat, have introduced restrictions to protect against its introduction and are screening native populations of ash trees grown abroad for resistance.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-04-04T12:21:39.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484839/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484839/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-23","Trees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the review from Keele University, published in the Journal of Ecology, warning that almost all ash trees in Europe will be wiped out due to the fungal disease ash dieback and the emerald ash borer beetle, and what plans they have to tackle these twin problems.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL7346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484840","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-06","<p>There are a number of considerations around whether to initiate the negotiation of reciprocal agreements for pensions and other social security benefits. These include reciprocity between the social security systems in the respective countries, the movement of people between the two countries, and the affordability of concluding and administering an agreement.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann",,"2016-04-06T12:27:01.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484840/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484840/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, for those countries and territories in which those in receipt of the UK state pension are subject to the frozen pensions regulations, what is the process necessary to negotiate reciprocal agreements for pensions to be uprated annually.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL7347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484841","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-08","<p>On 11 March, The Minister of State for Small Business, Industry and Enterprise wrote to potential candidates who have until 6 April to respond. We will issue a statement shortly after.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-04-08T11:21:34.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484841/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484841/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-23","Recall of Unsafe Products Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will announce the membership of the Steering Group referred to on page eight of the Government's Response to the Independent Recall Review by Lynn Faulds Wood, published by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills on 18 February.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL7348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484842","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-01","<p>The information requested is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-04-01T13:02:22.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484842/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484842/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","National Insurance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many National Insurance numbers were in use at the end of each of the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts",,"Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts","HL7349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484844","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-07","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has been consulting representative bodies through the Valuation Fiscal Forum over the last 18 months.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has not withdrawn valuation services that are most relevant to employee share ownership schemes.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has withdrawn valuation checks for income tax and PAYE as in most cases acceptable valuations were submitted, and therefore the service offered was not of sufficient value.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-04-07T15:43:17.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484844/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484844/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-23","Employee Ownership","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether there was any prior consultation before the decision was taken to end the post transaction valuation check and PAYE health check currently provided by HMRC with effect from 31 March 2016 and, if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts",,"Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts","HL7350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484845","Department for Education","false","2016-04-07","<p>As there is no formal definition of what constitutes “Craft, Creative Arts and Design”, it has not been possible to provide the information that is requested.</p>",,"Lord Nash","HL7352","2016-04-07T13:09:42.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484845/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484845/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-23","Arts: Qualifications","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many level 2 Craft, Creative Arts and Design (9.2) vocational qualifications were completed in each year since 2011 in England, Wales and Northern Ireland combined.","false","Biography information for Baroness Nye",,"Baroness Nye","HL7351"
