"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485726","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-11","<p>The United Nations report that 21.2 million people in Yemen require some kind of humanitarian assistance to meet their basic needs or protect their fundamental rights, as cited in the 2016 Humanitarian Response Plan (HRP). The government uses this UN report as one if its primary data sources.</p><p>We continue to call on other donors to step up. In July 2015 the Foreign and Development Secretaries wrote to international donors to raise the profile of Yemen’s humanitarian crisis and encourage more funding to the response. In September, the Development Secretary co-hosted a meeting on Yemen’s humanitarian crisis at the UN General Assembly, at which donors (including the UK) pledged an additional £85 million.</p><p>The Co-Chairs statement from the meeting can be found here: <a href="http://reliefweb.int/report/yemen/co-chairs-statement-ministerial-yemen-meeting-monday-28-september-2015" target="_blank">http://reliefweb.int/report/yemen/co-chairs-statement-ministerial-yemen-meeting-monday-28-september-2015</a></p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-11T12:14:57.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485726/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485726/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-23","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the humanitarian situation in Yemen; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","32340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485727","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-11","<p>DFID has provided £19,867 to support UNOCHA for its work in Libya since 1 April 2015. This was to provide surge support for coordination to UNOCHA during the production of the Humanitarian Response Plan. The secondment came to a close unexpectedly early. Following a decision by OCHA not to replace the coordinator, we have used some of the remaining funds to second an Emergency Health Sector Coordinator within WHO since November 2015 at a cost of £34,614 in response to priority needs. In addition, we are currently brokering a further surge secondment to OCHA and at this point in time the costs are not finalised.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-11T12:14:00.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485727/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485727/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-23","Libya: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 21 March 2016 to Question 31131, for what reason the amount of financial assistance her Department has provided to UNOCHA for its work in Libya since 1 April 2015 was not supplied in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","32261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485728","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-11","<p>In education, DFID is supporting the Government of Nigeria’s Safe Schools Initiative, which aims to restore safe access to learning for children affected by conflict. The Initiative has supported over 90,000 displaced children to return to school, providing learning materials and training teachers on psychosocial support. In health, DFID is supporting the International Committee of the Red Cross, who have helped restore basic health care services for 225,000 people affected by conflict, and provided 150,000 immunisations for children.</p><p> </p><p>All of our programmes, including those that assist internally displaced children, work with government authorities and other donors to influence national plans and strategies, and to strengthen education and health systems.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-11T15:52:02.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485728/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485728/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-23","Nigeria: Internally Displaced People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to assist the Nigerian government to support access for internally displaced children in that country to (a) education and (b) healthcare.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","32306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485729","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-11","<p>Negotiation of UK tax treaties is a matter for HM Revenue and Customs.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-11T12:15:36.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485729/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485729/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-23","Developing Countries: Double Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many full-time members of staff her Department employs in renegotiating tax treaties with developing countries.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","32391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485730","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-12","<p>The UK is committed to Palestinian development in Area C. We continue to urge the Government of Israel to develop improved mechanisms for zoning, planning and permitting in Area C for the benefit of the Palestinian population, including by facilitating local Palestinian participation in such processes. The UK has allocated £900,000 for the development of basic social infrastructure in areas which have an outline plan in the approval process, through an EU consortium. The EU consults with the local communities themselves and the Israeli authorities where necessary.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-12T12:39:03.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485730/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485730/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-23","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when the UK is joining the EU Consortium to support the construction of small-scale infrastructure in Area C; and whether such construction has received planning permission from the Israeli government.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","32417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485731","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-14","<p>This information is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-04-14T14:28:22.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485731/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485731/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-23","Armed Forces: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of non-combat related deaths in the UK military were given an inquiry by jury in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","32308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485732","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-11","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-11T14:17:58.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485732/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485732/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-23","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many appeal hearings at the First-tier Tribunal (Social Security and Child Support) were (a) withdrawn and (b) adjourned as a result of the Department for Work and Pensions not sending a representative in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","32293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485733","Leader of the House","false","2016-04-11","<p>The rules regarding the continuing work of departments during the statutory 28-day pre-referendum period are clearly set out in the Cabinet Secretary’s letter of 23 February 2016 to Permanent Secretaries, which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/502580/Jeremy_Heywood_to_Permanent_Secretaries_-_EU_Referendum_Guidance.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/502580/Jeremy_Heywood_to_Permanent_Secretaries_-_EU_Referendum_Guidance.pdf</a></p><p>It states that: ‘All EU and EU-related business, including negotiations in or with all EU institutions and other Member States, EU Council meetings and policy discussions within government will continue as usual throughout this period. The normal rules of collective responsibility apply and therefore the existing machinery of government for making policy on EU business will continue to function in the normal way, including Cabinet Committee clearance processes.’</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2016-04-11T14:27:25.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485733/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485733/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-03-23","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, if he will make it the policy of the Government not to bring forward regulations seeking to implement EU Directives until the outcome of the EU referendum is known.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","32458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485734","Prime Minister","false","2016-04-11","I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Illford South (Mr Gapes) during my Oral Statement today.","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-04-11T16:07:38.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485734/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485734/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-03-23","Anti-corruption Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether representatives of the UK's Crown Dependencies and Overseas Territories will be invited to the anti-corruption summit in May.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","32393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485735","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The publication of the guidance is the responsibility of the Secretary of State for the Department for Business Innovation and Skills (BIS).</p><p> </p><p>My officials have been working collaboratively with officials in BIS and the draft revised guidance has now been submitted to key stakeholders, including employee and employer representatives, for comment. BIS has stated that it remains on target to publish the guidance in spring 2016.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T13:10:43.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485735/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485735/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Shipping: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2016 to Question 25958, when he expects the revised guidance on the national minimum wage for seafarers to be published; and when he last discussed that matter with the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","32385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485736","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The bus market outside London is deregulated and decisions regarding service provision is primarily a commercial matter for bus operators. Decisions about the provision of subsidised services are a matter for individual English local authorities, in the light of their other spending priorities.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to supporting bus services in England. We are taking forward a Buses bill to provide local authorities with the tools they need to improve local bus services.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-11T13:03:22.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485736/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485736/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Bus Services: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of bus services in Middlesbrough, Redcar and Cleveland and Teesside.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","32397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485737","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Environmental Statement and Supplementary Environmental Statements for the Phase One hybrid Bill fully assessed the impact on air quality from HS2 construction. The method of assessment is specifically directed at the limit values set out in Annex II of Directive 2008/50/EC, and identifies whether the limit values are currently breached, anticipated to be breached in the future, and to what extent any breaches are affected by the construction of Phase One of HS2.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T15:30:59.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485737/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485737/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what evidence he has received to demonstrate  that the construction of Phase One of High Speed 2 will not breach the requirements of Directive 2008/50/EC on ambient air quality and cleaner air for Europe.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","32387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485738","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Environmental Statement and Supplementary Environmental Statements for the Phase One hybrid Bill fully assessed the impact on air quality from HS2 construction. Those assessments specifically considered the limit values set out in Annex II of Directive 2008/50/EC, and identified whether the limit values are currently breached, were anticipated to be breached in the future, and to what extent any breaches would be affected by the construction of Phase One of High Speed Two.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T15:27:40.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485738/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485738/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an assessment of whether the air quality objectives set out in Annex II of Directive 2008/50/EC on ambient air quality and cleaner air for Europe will be breached in any location scheduled to be affected by the construction of Phase One of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","32386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485739","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-12","<p>Connected and autonomous vehicles could potentially have significant impacts on traffic flow and road network efficiency. The government recognises that this is an important issue and needs to be better understood to properly inform long-term policy and investment decisions. For this reason, the Department for Transport is currently conducting research to explore the traffic flow impacts of connected and autonomous vehicles. This work is ongoing, and forms part of a much wider programme of research and development that the Government is supporting to examine the issues associated with these technologies.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-12T14:45:55.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485739/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485739/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Driverless Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential for driverless cars to improve the efficiency of use of road space on motorways.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","32419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485740","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-12","<p>The Department for Transport has not yet made an assessment of the potential for connected and autonomous vehicles to reduce motorway collisions. Research suggests that connected and autonomous vehicles will have a positive impact on safety - systems such as Advanced Emergency Braking are already acknowledged by some insurers to reduce collisions. However research in this area is limited by the extent of real world testing. The Government recognises the need to ensure that the implications of these technologies on safety are well-understood, and they can be introduced safely onto public roads. That is why the Department for Transport plans to conduct trials of driverless vehicles on the Strategic Road Network by the end of 2017, which will be delivered by Highways England. The Centre for Connected and Autonomous Vehicles also plans to do further research in this area, as part of a much wider programme of research and development that the Government is supporting to examine the issues associated with these technologies.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-12T14:53:38.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485740/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485740/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Driverless Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential for driverless cars to reduce motorway collisions.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","32420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485741","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-12","<p>Connected and autonomous vehicles could potentially have significant impacts on factors that affect the overall energy consumption and energy efficiency of road transport. The Department for Transport is currently conducting research to explore the energy impacts of connected and autonomous vehicles. This work is ongoing, and forms part of a much wider programme of research and development that the Government is supporting to examine the issues associated with these technologies. The Centre for Connected and Autonomous Vehicles also plans to do further research in this area.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-12T15:02:16.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485741/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485741/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Driverless Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential for driverless cars to increase energy efficiency.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","32421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485743","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Government continues to consider the large amount of very detailed analysis contained in the Airports Commission’s final report, including on flight paths, before taking any decisions on next steps. Ultimately, any proposals to alter the airport’s flightpaths would be subject to the Civil Aviation Authority’s Airspace Change Process which includes the need to consult those local communities affected.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T13:33:19.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485743/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485743/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many public and private hospitals lie under the Heathrow final approach flight paths; and how many such hospitals would lie under the proposed flightpaths should the third runway be approved.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","32254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485744","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>On 14 December 2015, the Government formally announced that it accepted the Airports Commission’s case for new runway capacity in the South East, as well as the Commission’s three shortlisted schemes - namely additional runways at Gatwick or Heathrow, or an extension to the existing northern runway at Heathrow. The Government will not be considering any other options.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T13:39:16.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485744/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485744/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Heathrow Hub runway extension is being considered as an alternative to a third runway.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","32255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485745","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>On 14 December 2015, the Government formally announced that it accepted the Airports Commission’s case for new runway capacity in the South East, as well as the Commission’s three shortlisted schemes. We continue to consider all three schemes, including a third runway at Heathrow. At the same time, it was also announced that the Department for Transport would prepare an airports national policy statement as the framework for implementing decisions on airport capacity in line with the Planning Act 2008.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T13:43:39.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485745/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485745/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what he expects the decision-making process after any announcement regarding a third runway at Heathrow to be.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","32256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485746","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The construction of Phase One of HS2 will not result in any household experiencing carbon monoxide levels in excess of the thresholds for that substance detailed in European Directive 2008/50/EC.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T15:24:56.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485746/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485746/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the construction activity required to construct Phase One of High Speed 2 will result in any household experiencing carbon monoxide levels in excess of the thresholds for that substance detailed in European Directive 2008/50/EC on ambient air quality and cleaner air for Europe.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","32241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485748","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-12","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer announced on 16 March 2016 as part of the Budget 2016 that the Government will be allocating a further £130 million to those authorities affected by this winter’s Storms. This funding is on top of the £49 million already committed to repair transport infrastructure damaged by Storms Desmond and Eva. This funding is being met by savings made by the Department for Transport in other transport programmes during the 2015/16 financial year.</p><p> </p><p>This funding is in addition to the £6.1 billion we are providing to local highway authorities in England for local highways maintenance between now and 2021.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-12T15:19:47.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485748/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485748/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer to Question 31603, from which funding stream the additional  £130 million funding for repair of roads and bridges damaged by Storms Desmond and Eva will be taken.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","32342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485749","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-12","<p>The Home Office, Civil Aviation Authority and the Police are currently engaged in discussions regarding the memorandum of understanding, a final document will be agreed and signed by all parties shortly.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-12T14:31:51.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485749/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485749/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2016 to Question 25277, when he expects the memorandum of understanding to be agreed.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","32352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485750","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-12","<p>The outcome of this risk assessment will be used to inform further research into and development of appropriate risk mitigation measures.</p><p> </p><p>As stated in my previous answer this work is ongoing and is kept under constant review.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-12T14:38:03.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485750/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485750/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2016 to Question 25276, on unmanned air vehicles: safety, when he expects his Department to complete the detailed analysis of risks posed by drones.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","32353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485751","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-12","<p>The alternative Colne Valley tunnelling scheme, as proposed by the London Borough of Hillingdon (LBH), has been assessed and evidence was presented to the House of Commons HS2 Phase One Bill Select Committee. The Select Committee highlighted a number of concerns with the tunnel scheme in their statement on the 15th July 2015 which concluded that ‘our overall view is that a convincing case for a tunnel instead of the viaduct has not been made.’ Importantly, the Select Committee noted that the evidence was that a tunnel would not eliminate the impact of construction works in Hillingdon and surrounding areas.</p><p> </p><p>However, HS2 Ltd is currently undertaking a study with LBH to identify how the HS2 construction impacts in Hillingdon can be further reduced. The results from this study are due to be reported in May 2016.</p><p> </p><p>In the meantime, the Secretary of State is happy to meet the hon. Member for Richmond Park, the hon. Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip, the hon. Member for Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner, and the Leader of Hillingdon Council.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-12T14:18:18.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485751/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485751/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-23","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will assess the alternative Colne Valley tunnelling scheme for High Speed 2 as proposed by Hillingdon Council; and if he will meet the hon. Member for Richmond Park, the Leader of Hillingdon Council and the hon. Member for Uxbridge and Ruislip Northwood and Pinner to discuss that alternative.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","32310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485752","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>The available information on the number of people who have completed the Work Programme is published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/WorkProg/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/WorkProg/tabtool.html</a></p><p>The information requested for those who stopped claiming Employment and Support Allowance after participation in the Work Programme is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-11T12:46:14.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485752/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485752/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Employment and Support Allowance: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employment support allowance claimants in (a) Scotland (b) Glasgow and (c) Glasgow Central constituency stopped claiming that allowance after participation in the Work Programme.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","32348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485753","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>The information requested is not available. However there will be Targeted Affordability Funding available to support areas where higher rent increases are causing a shortage of affordable accommodation.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-11T11:07:43.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485753/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485753/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 14 March 2016 to Question 29818, what assessment he has made of the effect of a four-year freeze in local housing allowance (LHA) rates on people that rely on LHA if the cost of renting in the private rented sector continues to rise; and whether the four-year freeze will disproportionally affect those living in houses with more than four bedrooms.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","32377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485754","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-11T14:46:28.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485754/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485754/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Work Programme: European Social Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on European Social Fund allocations for the Work programme.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","32347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485755","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>The information requested is not available because individual claimants’ circumstances can change as they move in and out of work or their earnings change. We have contacted all claimants who are in work and reporting earnings to make them aware of this change, which will affect a subset of that population.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-11T12:55:11.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485755/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485755/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Universal Credit: Wythenshawe and Sale East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in Wythenshawe and Sale East constituency who are existing universal credit claimants and who are in work will have their universal credit decreased as a result of changes to the work allowance taking effect in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","32339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485756","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-04-11T09:56:34.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485756/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485756/answer","UKSA response to 32337.pdf","UKSA response to 32337.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Employment","UKSA Letter to Member - Employment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485756/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-23","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many disabled people have found employment in the (a) private, (b) public and (c) charity sector in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","32337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485757","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-15","<p>We have a number of pension service telephony lines including the Pension Tracing Service; International Pension Claims/Changes; International Pension Enquiries; State Pension Claims; and State Pension changes. We conduct an annual DWP Customer Satisfaction Survey which ensures that we are delivering against our customer charter.</p><p> </p><p>All our Pension Service telephony services are subject to continuous improvement to improve our service delivery.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-15T13:46:33.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485757/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485757/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Pension Service: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent representations he has received on the effectiveness of the Pension Service helpline.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","32235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485758","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Universal Credit online application form is designed around user needs and over 90% of claims to Universal Credit have been made online. People without digital skills will be offered support to make and manage their Universal Credit (UC) claim online, and to acquire and to improve their digital skills. A telephone helpline is also available for claimants who cannot use the online service.</p><p>We have no evidence of any eligible claimants who have failed to claim due to the complexity of the Universal Credit application form.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-11T12:55:54.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485758/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485758/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the ability of prospective claimants to complete the online application form for universal credit; and if he will estimate the number of eligible claimants who have failed to claim due to the complexity of that application form.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","32228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485759","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>We have completed the planning for researching the impact of the ILF’s closure; we will publish the findings when the research is complete.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-11T13:58:03.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485759/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485759/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Independent Living Fund: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 29 February 2016 to Question 28404, on Independent Living Fund, if he will publish (a) the timescale and (b) the terms of reference of the research which the Government plans to conduct.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","32277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485760","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>An individual can submit a new claim for Employment and Support Allowance at any time after being found fit for work following a Work Capability Assessment.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-11T10:42:51.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485760/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485760/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how long after being found to be ineligible for employment and support allowance as a result of a work capability assessment can an individual submit a new claim.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","32294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485761","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>Following an internal review of Access to Work, a number of changes and customer service improvements were announced in March 2015. In support of our next stage of continuous improvement of Access to Work, we have commissioned independent business analysts to provide expert advice on how Access to Work can best deliver the Government’s ambition to increase numbers supported by the scheme by 65% over the course of the Parliament, and beyond.</p><p>This work is still on-going and details of the contract can be found at <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/e06d7b31-1135-42c9-a81b-854984be1137" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/e06d7b31-1135-42c9-a81b-854984be1137</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-11T13:18:55.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485761/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485761/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Access to Work Programme: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department spent on consultancy costs examining possible proposals for the future of the Access to Work scheme.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","32288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485762","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>a) and b) Based on the latest available figures from the Department’s Family Resources Survey 2013/2014, an estimated 11.9 million people in the UK reported a disability. The table below provides more detailed information about the types of impairment that disabled people reported.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1: Disability prevalence disaggregated by impairment type UK, 2013/14</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Millions of individuals</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Impairment type</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Vision</p></td><td><p>1.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hearing</p></td><td><p>1.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mobility</p></td><td><p>6.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dexterity</p></td><td><p>3.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Learning</p></td><td><p>1.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Memory</p></td><td><p>1.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mental health</p></td><td><p>2.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Stamina/breathing/fatigue</p></td><td><p>4.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Social/behavioural</p></td><td><p>0.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>1.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All with at least one impairment</p></td><td><p>11.9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Family Resources Survey 2013/14</p><p> </p><p>Respondents can report, and be affected by, more than one type of impairment.</p><p> </p><p>c) Using the FRS an estimated 2.7 million people in the UK reported both a physical and mental disability. This estimate includes all individuals currently living in private households. It does not include individuals living in communal establishments (e.g. care homes).</p><p> </p><p>For the purposes of this analysis, the following categories have been classified as physical disabilities;</p><p>Vision, Hearing, Mobility, Dexterity, and Stamina/Breathing/Fatigue.</p><p> </p><p>The following categories have been classified as mental disabilities;</p><p>Learning, Memory, Mental Health, and Social/Behavioural</p><p> </p><p>Note that disabilities classified as &quot;other&quot; have not been included in part c).</p><p> </p><p>The department cannot provide figures in the format requested for Twickenham.</p><p> </p><p>Aggregate level estimates of people with disability aged 16-64 in Twickenham can be found on the Nomis website based on the Annual Population Survey: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/select/getdatasetbytheme.asp?opt=3&amp;theme=&amp;subgrp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/query/select/getdatasetbytheme.asp?opt=3&amp;theme=&amp;subgrp</a>=</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-11T13:52:07.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485762/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485762/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent estimate his Department has made of the number of people with a (a) physical disability, (b) mental disability and (c) physical and mental disability in (i) the UK and (ii) Twickenham constituency.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","32462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485763","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-14","<p>There are no targets set for providers in relation to the closing of benefit claims, though for a job to be eligible for outcome payments, providers must support people into enough work to take them off out-of-work benefits.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-14T16:31:36.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485763/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485763/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department sets targets related to the closing of benefit claims of people referred to the work programme.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","32431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485764","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>Personal Independence Payment (PIP) will be introduced in Northern Ireland later this year. Information regarding Northern Ireland is a matter for the Northern Ireland Office.</p><p> </p><p>The number of people in receipt of Disability Living Allowance by geography and age is published and available at: <a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/dla/tabtool_dla.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/dla/tabtool_dla.html</a>. Guidance for users is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance</a>.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Information on the number of claimants in receipt of PIP, by geography and age, is available from Stat-Xplore. <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-11T13:48:17.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485764/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485764/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people (a) of working age, (b) of retirement age and (c) younger than working age are in receipt of (i) disability living allowance and (ii) personal independence payments in (A) the UK and (B) Twickenham constituency.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","32461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485766","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>As confirmed by my right honourable friend the Secretary of State in his statement to the House on 21 March, the proposed changes to PIP will not be going ahead.</p><p> </p><p>We spend around £50bn every year on benefits alone to support people with disabilities or health conditions, with spending on Personal Independence Payment (PIP) and Disability Living Allowance (DLA) having increased by more than £3 billion since 2010. The government is committed to talking to disabled people, their representatives, healthcare professionals and employers to ensure the welfare system works better with the health and social care systems and provides help and support to those who need it most.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","32380 ; 32455","2016-04-11T13:40:21.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485766/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485766/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Personal Independence Payment: Disability Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 1.7 of his Department's response to the consultation on aids and appliances and the daily living component of personal independence payments, published in March 2016, if he will publish the equality analysis referred to in that paragraph.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","32456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485767","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>As confirmed by my right honourable friend the Secretary of State in his statement to the House on 21 March, the proposed changes to PIP will not be going ahead.</p><p> </p><p>We spend around £50bn every year on benefits alone to support people with disabilities or health conditions, with spending on Personal Independence Payment (PIP) and Disability Living Allowance (DLA) having increased by more than £3 billion since 2010. The government is committed to talking to disabled people, their representatives, healthcare professionals and employers to ensure the welfare system works better with the health and social care systems and provides help and support to those who need it most.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","32380 ; 32456","2016-04-11T13:40:21.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485767/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485767/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Personal Independence Payment: Disability Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 4.10 of his Department's response to its consultation on aids and appliances and the daily living component of personal independence payment, published in March 2016, if he will publish the raw data referred to in that paragraph; and whether that data was subject to peer review.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","32455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485768","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Department held stakeholder events in Birmingham, Cardiff, Edinburgh, Leeds and London. These were public meetings open to anyone who wished to attend; this was publicised on Gov.uk. Representatives of the following organisations requested to do so:</p><p> </p><p>Aberdeen City Council</p><p>Action for Blind People</p><p>The Action Group</p><p>Carers Support (Bexley)</p><p>Cheshire Centre for Independent Living</p><p>Citizens Advice Bureau</p><p>Coventry Law Centre</p><p>Child Poverty Action Group Scotland</p><p>Community Navigator Services</p><p>Crohn’s and Colitis UK</p><p>Deaf Sector Partnership/Scottish Council on Deafness</p><p>DeafBlind Scotland</p><p>DeafBlind UK</p><p>Deafconnect</p><p>Elcena Jeffers Foundation</p><p>Enable Scotland</p><p>Enfield Disability Action</p><p>Gateway Housing</p><p>Glasgow City Council</p><p>Housing Options Scotland</p><p>Inclusion Scotland</p><p>Lothian Centre for Inclusive Living</p><p>Macmillan Cancer Support</p><p>Maggie’s Centres</p><p>Motor Neurone Disease Association</p><p>Multiple Sclerosis Scotland</p><p>Multiple Sclerosis Society</p><p>National AIDS Trust</p><p>Royal National Institute of Blind People</p><p>Scope</p><p>The Scottish Government</p><p>Sense</p><p>South Lanarkshire Council</p><p>Spinal Injuries Association</p><p>Social Security Advisory Committee</p><p>Swansea Council</p><p>Welfare Benefits Unit</p><p>Welsh Government</p><p>West Lothian Council</p><p>Wolverhampton City Council</p><p> </p><p>Departmental officials also held one-to-one meetings with Scope, RNIB, Disability Rights UK, the Disability Benefits Consortium (an umbrella group of over 60 organisations), and Scottish and Welsh government officials. A meeting was also held specifically for members of the PIP Implementation Stakeholder Forum Working Group. Meetings were also held with both assessment providers, Atos and Capita, to discuss the impact of any policy change on the delivery of assessments.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-11T14:09:16.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485768/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485768/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Personal Independence Payment: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish (a) the criteria used to select organisations invited to attend and (b) the organisations that attended personal independence payments consultation stakeholder events in January 2016.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","32454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485769","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>The earnings limit for Carer’s Allowance which is not linked to the number of hours worked is currently £110 per week (net of certain expenses). It was increased to £110 in April 2015 – an increase of nearly 8%, which far outstripped the growth in earnings.</p><p>The Government keeps the earnings limit under review and keeps under consideration whether an increase in the threshold is warranted and affordable.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-11T14:45:29.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485769/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485769/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Carer's Allowance: Uprating","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will raise the threshold for carer's allowance to take into account increases in the national minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Simon Hart","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart","32372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485770","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>The time period for the consultation was decided in line with the Government’s consultation principles guidance. This advises that consultations should typically run for between 2 and 12 weeks, but that “the timing and length of a consultation should be decided on a case-by-case basis; there is no set formula for establishing the right length”.</p><p>As we were consulting on the specific and discrete issue of how aids and appliances are accounted for when determining eligibility to the daily living component, 6 weeks was felt to be an appropriate length.</p><p>As the consultation ran over Christmas this period was extended by 8 days, which is why the consultation ran for 7 weeks and one day. The length of the consultation was determined by the Government, as is standard practice. There have been no discussions with Compact Voice on this issue.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-11T14:00:03.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485770/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485770/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Personal Independence Payment: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions his Department has had with Compact Voice about the duration of the formal personal independent payment consultation.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","32383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485771","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>Information on average weekly payments of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) is not published but can be calculated from the available claimant data extractable from Stat-Xplore (<a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>) and the amount of benefit paid by component combination. At the end of January 2016 the average amount payable to PIP recipients in Great Britain was £88.70 per week and £88.14 per week in the Twickenham parliamentary constituency.</p><p> </p><p>Personal Independence Payment (PIP) will be introduced in Northern Ireland later this year and will be a matter for the Northern Ireland Office.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-11T14:04:41.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485771/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485771/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average value is of a personal independence payment in (a) the UK and (b) Twickenham constituency.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","32381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485772","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-11","<p>As confirmed by my right honourable friend the Secretary of State in his statement to the House on 21 March, the proposed changes to PIP will not be going ahead.</p><p> </p><p>We spend around £50bn every year on benefits alone to support people with disabilities or health conditions, with spending on Personal Independence Payment (PIP) and Disability Living Allowance (DLA) having increased by more than £3 billion since 2010. The government is committed to talking to disabled people, their representatives, healthcare professionals and employers to ensure the welfare system works better with the health and social care systems and provides help and support to those who need it most.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","32455 ; 32456","2016-04-11T13:40:21.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485772/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485772/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","Personal Independence Payment: Disability Aids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's consultation on aids and appliances and the daily living component of personal independence payments, Cm 9171, if he will publish the impact assessment prepared for the five options in that consultation.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","32380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485773","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-15","<p>Following the Pensions Act 1995, which set out the timetable for women’s State Pension age to rise from 60 to 65, changes to State Pension age were communicated in State Pension estimates issued to individuals on request. These estimates provided individuals with their most up-to-date date of reaching State Pension age. Since April 2000, the Department has issued more than 11.5 million personalised State Pension statements to people who requested them.</p><p>Independent evidence submitted to the Work and Pensions Select Committee demonstrates that there were several mentions of State Pension age equalisation in the national broadsheet and tabloid press between 1993 and 2006.</p><p>The Department also ran a pensions education campaign in 2004, which included informing people of the future equalisation of State Pension age. A 2007 DWP report, Attitudes to pensions: The 2006 survey, reported that 86 per cent of women aged 55-64 and 90 per cent aged 45-54 were aware that the State Pension age will increase in future.</p><p>The Government sent letters to women affected by changes in the 1995 Act between April 2009 and March 2011 using the address details held by HMRC at that time.</p><p>The timetable for equalising State Pension age at 65 for women and men and for the increase to 66 was accelerated by the Pensions Act 2011 following sharp increases in life expectancy projections. A concession worth £1.1 billion was made prior to the passing of the 2011 Act which capped the maximum delay that anyone would face in claiming their State Pension to 18 months rather than two years, relative to the previous timetable. The Government sent letters between January 2012 and November 2013 to all those directly affected to inform them of the changes to their State Pension age.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-15T12:22:06.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485773/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/485773/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-23","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the adequacy and timeliness of information given to women born in the 1950s of changes to the age at which they become eligible for the state pension; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Damian Green","Ashford","Damian Green","32272"
