"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484377","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-12","<p>Ministry of Justice officials met Professor Walton and others on 12 October last year to discuss his report, but the Ministry of Justice did not agree with his conclusions. Our changes to no win no fee deals have tackled the increasing costs of litigation. We delayed bringing the law in for insolvency proceedings to allow the industry time to prepare. The no win no fee reforms in Part 2 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 will come into force for insolvency proceedings on 6 April this year.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","32048 ; 32049","2016-04-12T14:21:44.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484377/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484377/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-22","Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the report by Professor Walton, entitled The likely effect of the Jackson reforms on insolvency litigation - an empirical investigation, published in 2013, what his policy is on each of the conclusions of that report.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","32047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484378","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-12","<p>Ministry of Justice officials met Professor Walton and others on 12 October last year to discuss his report, but the Ministry of Justice did not agree with his conclusions. Our changes to no win no fee deals have tackled the increasing costs of litigation. We delayed bringing the law in for insolvency proceedings to allow the industry time to prepare. The no win no fee reforms in Part 2 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 will come into force for insolvency proceedings on 6 April this year.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","32047 ; 32049","2016-04-12T14:21:44.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484378/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484378/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-22","Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the report by Professor Walton, entitled The likely effect of the Jackson reforms on insolvency litigation - an empirical investigation, published in 2013, what the evidential basis is for his policy on each of the conclusions of that report.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","32048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484379","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-12","<p>Ministry of Justice officials met Professor Walton and others on 12 October last year to discuss his report, but the Ministry of Justice did not agree with his conclusions. Our changes to no win no fee deals have tackled the increasing costs of litigation. We delayed bringing the law in for insolvency proceedings to allow the industry time to prepare. The no win no fee reforms in Part 2 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 will come into force for insolvency proceedings on 6 April this year.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","32047 ; 32048","2016-04-12T14:21:44.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484379/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484379/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-22","Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on what date his Department met Professor Walton to discuss the findings of his interim report on the insolvency litigation landscape, published on 10 December 2015.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","32049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484380","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-24","<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) publish data on the total value of the UK’s import and export trade in goods by region:</p><p>https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/RTS/Pages/default.aspx</p><p> </p><p>The latest data for 2015 shows that the value of goods exports to the EU as a proportion of total goods exports is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Region</p></td><td><p>Goods exports to the EU (£000s)</p></td><td><p>Total goods exports (£000s)</p></td><td><p>%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>7,001,603</p></td><td><p>12,141,343</p></td><td><p>57.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>11,578,566</p></td><td><p>24,838,093</p></td><td><p>46.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire</p></td><td><p>7,785,133</p></td><td><p>16,575,590</p></td><td><p>47.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>8,684,722</p></td><td><p>19,318,347</p></td><td><p>45.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>12,035,888</p></td><td><p>28,964,501</p></td><td><p>41.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>11,411,149</p></td><td><p>21,327,266</p></td><td><p>53.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>12,727,129</p></td><td><p>32,428,175</p></td><td><p>39.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>19,003,485</p></td><td><p>40,521,161</p></td><td><p>46.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>9,718,023</p></td><td><p>15,272,223</p></td><td><p>63.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>5,024,163</p></td><td><p>12,200,136</p></td><td><p>41.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>6,719,840</p></td><td><p>17,467,865</p></td><td><p>38.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p>3,462,494</p></td><td><p>6,327,320</p></td><td><p>54.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The ONS publish regional GVA on an annual basis. The latest data available is for 2014: http://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/grossv