"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484410","Department of Health","false","2016-03-29","<p>Think Autism the updated strategy for adults with autism in England set out a clear cross Government programme of action, developed by people with autism, their families and carers, to support local authorities, the National Health Service, and other public services to improve the lives of people with autism. In addition, last year, NHS England commissioned the world's first Learning Disability Mortality Review Programme to support local areas to review deaths of people with learning disabilities, including those with autism, and to use the information to improve service provision so that physical and mental health problems can be identified and addressed. This programme is currently being piloted and will be rolled out more widely in due course.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-03-29T14:24:24.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484410/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484410/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-22","Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps are being taken to improve the care offered to people with autism in order to reduce the difference in life expectancy between people with and people without autism.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","32130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484411","Home Office","false","2016-03-31","<p>HM Government publish data on asylum intake which can be found at: Immigration statistics, October to December 2015: data tables - Publications - GOV.UK . The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-31T14:10:56.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484411/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484411/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-22","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 15 March 2016 to Question 30557, how many people who have arrived in the UK through the camp in Calais have successfully claimed asylum in the UK since June 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","32158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484412","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-29","<p>All equipment being gifted is non-lethal in nature, and includes night vision goggles, global positioning sets (GPS), helmets, body armour, ruggedized laptops, large tents, heating units, cold weather clothing and individual first aid kits.</p><p>This equipment has helped save lives in contested areas in the Donbas. Given its non-lethal nature, we see no need routinely to monitor its location and usage.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-03-29T15:01:51.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484412/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484412/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-22","Ukraine: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he plans to take to monitor the location and use of the recently announced military equipment being given to Ukraine.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","32159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484413","Department of Health","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Department has no current plans to collect information on the numbers of foreign medical graduates who take up employment in the National Health Service.</p><p>Non-European Economic Area (EEA) nationals pay full tuition fees when studying medicine in the United Kingdom and make a contribution to the UK economy. The Government has no current plans to introduce legislation to secure better value for money from non-EEA nationals studying medicine in the UK.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-24T16:04:43.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484413/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484413/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-22","Medicine: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2016 to Question 28925, if his Department will begin collecting information on the proportion of foreign graduates who take up employment in the NHS; and if he will bring forward legislative proposals to ensure that the public purse receives value for money when subsidising medicine degrees for foreign nationals.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","32167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484414","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-30","<p>While Greece remains in the euro, its financial stability is the responsibility of the euro area. The UK Government has secured a deal that protects UK taxpayers from any risk from financing euro area bailouts now and in the future. The UK is therefore not involved in the review of Greece’s euro area bailout package agreed in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Ministers and officials routinely meet with international counterparts to discuss economic and financial issues within the euro area and wider European Union, including ongoing financial assistance programmes.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-30T13:41:07.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484414/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484414/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-22","Greece: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what reports he has received on progress made by Greece in implementing the conditions of the 2015 EU bailout package; and if he will press for steps to improve transparency and monitor use of the bailout funds.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","32112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484415","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-30","<p>The UK and Turkey work in close partnership to stop foreign terrorist fighters and extremist travellers from crossing the border between Syria and Turkey, including through practical cooperation between our police and security forces.</p><p>The Turkish authorities are taking significant measures to prevent illegal crossings from Turkey to the conflict zone, including the deployment of additional personnel. Physical security at border crossings between Syria and Turkey is improving, although sections of the border remain porous.</p><p>Between January and December 2015, 913 foreign nationals who are members of Daesh were arrested in Turkey, 435 of whom were caught passing to Syria.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-03-30T12:21:03.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484415/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484415/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-22","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent progress has been made in preventing members of the Islamic State/Daesh from travelling across the border between Syria and Turkey.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","32129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484416","Department for Education","false","2016-04-12","<p>Revenue from the soft drinks industry levy will be used to double the PE and sport premium for primary schools to £320m a year from September 2017, enabling them to improve the quality and breadth of PE and sport they offer. It will also provide up to £285m a year to enable up to a quarter of secondary schools to extend their school day to offer a wider range of activities, including sports clubs. Further details will be announced in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-04-12T13:18:02.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484416/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484416/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-22","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what criteria the Government plans to use to calculate each school's allocation of funds raised from the soft drinks industry levy for school sports.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","32098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484417","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-30","<p>HM Treasury monitor the impact of developments in the global economy, including those in the Euro Area, on an ongoing basis.</p><p> </p><p>To date, the European Central Bank have not implemented “Helicopter Money”. The ECB President noted on March 10 that the ECB “hadn’t really studied the concept”.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-30T13:37:20.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484417/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484417/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-22","Monetary Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the UK economy of the use of helicopter funds by the European Central Bank.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","32099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484418","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer has frequent discussions with the Governor of the Bank of England on a wide range of issues relating to the UK economy.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-29T10:51:49.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484418/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484418/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-22","Monetary Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Governor of the Bank of England on the potential use of helicopter funds in the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","32100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484419","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Home Office maintains active partnerships with the local authorities that have volunteered to become dispersal areas across the UK and funds regional Strategic Migration Partnerships (SMPs) to plan the dispersal of asylum seekers across the region. The partnerships consider the impact on communities and local services so that adjustments can be made where appropriate. This ensures that community cohesion, social welfare and safety issues are properly considered.</p><p>SMPs act as a focal point allowing the sharing of expertise and vital information between the Home Office, its asylum accommodation providers, local government, health, education and the police, ensuring coordinated planning and leadership on asylum dispersion. They also consider other funded objectives such as initiatives in support of visa policy; modern slavery; immigration sanctions and improvement; vulnerable children (including Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children) and adults; No Recourse to Public Funds policies of local government; EU migration and integration.</p><p>The Home Office, our housing contractors and the SMPs work closely with local authorities to ensure we can accommodate asylum seekers in appropriate accommodation.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","32194","2016-04-11T16:14:11.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484419/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484419/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-22","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure that local authorities are properly informed and involved in decisions to distribute asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","32107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484420","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Home Office maintains active partnerships with the local authorities that have volunteered to become dispersal areas across the UK and funds regional Strategic Migration Partnerships (SMPs) to plan the dispersal of asylum seekers across the region. The partnerships consider the impact on communities and local services so that adjustments can be made where appropriate. This ensures that community cohesion, social welfare and safety issues are properly considered.</p><p>SMPs act as a focal point allowing the sharing of expertise and vital information between the Home Office, its asylum accommodation providers, local government, health, education and the police, ensuring coordinated planning and leadership on asylum dispersion. They also consider other funded objectives such as initiatives in support of visa policy; modern slavery; immigration sanctions and improvement; vulnerable children (including Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children) and adults; No Recourse to Public Funds policies of local government; EU migration and integration.</p><p>The Home Office, our housing contractors and the SMPs work closely with local authorities to ensure we can accommodate asylum seekers in appropriate accommodation.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","32107","2016-04-11T16:14:11.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484420/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484420/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-22","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure that local authorities have appropriate resources to support and deal with increased demand for their services by asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","32194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484421","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>Under the COMPASS contracts, providers are allowed to use contingency accommodation to cope with unanticipated increase in demand, but we have made clear to providers that this is only ever acceptable in exceptional situations and asylum seekers must be moved to appropriate longer term accommodation as soon as possible. Providers will inform local authorities about short term contingency accommodation prior to its use.</p><p>Our records indicate that there are currently 22 hotels in use across 10 local authorities. This is provisional management information that is subject to daily change. It has not been assured to the standard of Official Statistics</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-11T16:13:27.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484421/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484421/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-22","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the level of hotel use to house asylum seekers is in each local authority area.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","32195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484422","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Government continues to consider the large amount of very detailed analysis contained in the Airports Commission’s Final Report, including on housing demand and loss, before taking any decisions on next steps<strong>.</strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-11T13:28:42.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484422/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484422/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-22","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the availability of housing of plans to demolish homes in the event of a third runway being built at Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","32051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484423","Department of Health","false","2016-03-24","<p>In November 2015, the HIV Prevention Innovation fund announced one year’s funding for seven projects led by voluntary sector organisations. Project funding included an allocation for monitoring and evaluation of their activities and projects have been asked to submit regular monitoring reports to Public Health England. Projects will be asked to report the outcome of their work at the end of their contract. These results will be combined into a single report, which will draw out and highlight important learning from all projects, to be presented and published before the end of the 2016/17 financial year.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-24T15:00:49.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484423/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484423/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-22","HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what mechanisms are in place to monitor the use of HIV innovation funding; and when he plans to (a) conduct and (b) publish his review of the projects that have received such funding.","false","Biography information for Mike Freer","Finchley and Golders Green","Mike Freer","32055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484424","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-11","<p>Defra is working with DECC towards the Government’s Emissions Reduction Plan. This will be the successor to the 2011 Carbon Plan, which is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-carbon-plan-reducing-greenhouse-gas-emissions--2" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-carbon-plan-reducing-greenhouse-gas-emissions--2</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Plan will set out our policies and proposals for meeting the UK’s carbon budgets.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-04-11T09:50:19.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484424/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484424/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-22","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her Department's contribution is to the Government's emissions reduction plan; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","32143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484425","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Department of Business, Innovation and Skills HQ has (a) 45% of its apprentices who are over the age of 25 and (b) all of its apprentices are paid at a rate which exceeds the National Living Wage.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-11T16:22:34.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484425/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484425/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-22","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of civil service apprentices in his Department are (a) over the age of 25 and (b) paid at the rate of the national living wage.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","32110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484426","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-21","<p>Since 2010 BIS has appointed a total of 89 apprentices, of which 44 were new appointments and 45 were existing civil servants taking up an apprenticeship.</p><p> </p><p>BIS is committed to meet the apprenticeship target of 2.3% of the workforce.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-21T15:26:35.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484426/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484426/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484426/answer/previousversion/54590","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-22","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many civil service apprentices have been appointed by his Department to date.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","32111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484427","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>All Cabinet Office costs are published in its annual report and accounts available on the GOV.UK website.</p><p>The Anti-Corruption Champion has had a range of meetings with Ministers and officials from other government departments, as well as representatives from civil society and business, both in the United Kingdom (UK) and overseas.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","32149","2016-04-11T09:54:48.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484427/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484427/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-22","Anti-corruption Champion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 21 March 2016 to Question 31068, how many meetings the Government's Anti-Corruption Champion had with (a) Ministers and officials of other government departments and (b) representatives from civil society and business between July 2015 and the end of February 2016.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","32148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484428","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>All Cabinet Office costs are published in its annual report and accounts available on the GOV.UK website.</p><p>The Anti-Corruption Champion has had a range of meetings with Ministers and officials from other government departments, as well as representatives from civil society and business, both in the United Kingdom (UK) and overseas.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","32148","2016-04-11T09:54:48.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484428/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484428/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-22","Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 21 March 2016 to Question 31069 on corruption, what the usual practice is for disclosing such costs.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","32149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484429","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-24","<p>Government policy is to move the Green Investment Bank (GIB) in to the private sector. Following a sale, GIB’s contractual liabilities will be funded by its new shareholders. To the extent that HM Government retains a minority stake, the Government will contribute funds towards those contractual commitments on a pro rata basis for UK based investments.</p><p>Separately, as part of the sale process, the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) has entered into an agreement with Poyry (provider of electricity market reports and price forecasting) (electricity market report and associated price forecast provider) (electricity market report and associated price forecast provider)(electricity market report and associated price forecast provider)to share information with potential bidders to help them to undertake due diligence. This agreement requires BIS to provide an indemnity to Poyry in relation to any resulting liability Poyry might incur. My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills set out details of the indemnity in his written ministerial statement of 21 March (HCWS633) including his view that the likelihood of it being called upon is low. A Departmental minute explaining the procedure followed and describing the liabilities undertaken has also been placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-24T16:28:20.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484429/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484429/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-22","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimates his Department has made of the range for the value of liabilities arising from the sale of the Green Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","32151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484430","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-11","<p>I am withholding publication of the UK Armed Forces' Incident Reporting Standing Operating Procedure, which contains the civilian casualty review process, as disclosure would or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness, or security of our Armed Forces.</p><p>The UK takes all allegations of civilian casualties very seriously. Robust processes are in place to review reports of civilian casualties and to launch investigations where required.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-04-11T15:22:44.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484430/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484430/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-22","Rules of Engagement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will place a copy of his Department's (a) civilian casualty review procedure and (b) standard operating procedure in the Library.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","32193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484431","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-11","<p>The MQ-9 Users Group primarily discussed generic, future interoperability between US, UK, French and Italian Reaper operators, particularly in terms of software standards, logistics and training. The sharing of assets in Syria, Iraq and Libya was therefore not discussed explicitly.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-04-11T15:27:09.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484431/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484431/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-22","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 23886, whether asset-sharing in Syria, Iraq or Libya was considered at the meeting of the Reaper User Group that took place on 14 to 18 March.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","32178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484432","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-11","<p>No. Military action is authorised in accordance with the Rules of Engagement which I approve in accordance with the legal position.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-04-11T15:26:39.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484432/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484432/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-22","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 10 March 2016 to Question 30084, if he will make the Attorney General's advice available for inspection by the (a) Chief of the Air Staff (b) Deputy Commander of Operations and (c) Staff Branch Air Command responsible for authorisation of the drone strike which killed Reyaad Khan on 21 August 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","32179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484433","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-11","<p>We work closely with the United States: we do not, however, comment on the specific details of US intentions.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-04-11T15:27:44.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484433/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484433/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-22","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government approved or was consulted on the US airstrike in Syria that killed Junaid Hussain on 24 August 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","32208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484434","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-11","<p>Estimates of the number of taxpayers at each income tax rate band are published in HM Revenue and Customs' National Statistics which are available on the internet.</p><p> </p><p>The figures at UK level are published in table 2.1:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/number-of-individual-income-taxpayers-by-marginal-rate-gender-and-age" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/number-of-individual-income-taxpayers-by-marginal-rate-gender-and-age</a></p><p> </p><p>Breakdowns by country and region are published in table 2.2 including the West Midlands, which contains the parliamentary constituency of Solihull:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/number-of-individual-income-taxpayers-by-marginal-rate-gender-and-age-by-country" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/number-of-individual-income-taxpayers-by-marginal-rate-gender-and-age-by-country</a></p><p> </p><p>The latest available published data shows a projection of 314,000 higher rate taxpayers in the West Midlands in 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>These estimates are based on the 2012-13 Survey of Personal Incomes, projected to 2015-16 using economic assumptions consistent with the Office for Budget Responsibility’s March 2015 economic and fiscal outlook.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury does not publish this information at constituency level.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-11T13:41:57.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484434/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484434/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-22","Income Tax: Solihull","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many higher-rate taxpayers there are in Solihull.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","32211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484435","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-13","<p>The £300 increase in the personal allowance announced at Budget 16 is estimated to have reduced income tax for 28.9 million income tax payers in 2017-18. Of these individuals, 2.4 million live in the West Midlands region, which includes the Parliamentary Constituency of Solihull.</p><p> </p><p>These estimates are based on the 2013-14 Survey of Personal Incomes, projected to 2017-18 using economic assumptions consistent with the Office for Budget Responsibility’s March 2016 economic and fiscal outlook.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury does not publish this information at constituency level.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-13T10:01:34.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484435/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484435/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-22","Income Tax: Solihull","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of people in Solihull who will pay less income tax as a result of the increase in the personal allowance announced in Budget 2016.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","32212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484436","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-12","<p>The Government has announced it will be introducing a new Lifetime ISA, providing savers with the flexibility to save towards a first home and retirement at the same time.</p><p> </p><p>Savers will be able to transfer savings from other ISAs as one way of funding their Lifetime ISA. These contributions will count towards the £4,000 Lifetime ISA limit and will receive a bonus. In line with existing rules, transfers from previous years’ ISA contributions will not count towards that year’s £20,000 overall ISA limit.</p><p> </p><p>During the 2017-18 tax year only, those with a Help to Buy: ISA will be able to transfer in the savings they have built up before 6 April 2017 to the Lifetime ISA, and still save an additional £4,000 into a Lifetime ISA in that year. This means the whole amount will benefit from the 25% government bonus. Individuals will not be able to use a government bonus from both a Help to Buy: ISA and a Lifetime ISA to buy their first home.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-12T13:42:40.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484436/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484436/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-22","Individual Savings Accounts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on allowing for integration of the lifetime ISA and existing standard ISAs.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","32133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484437","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Government is creating a new Lifetime ISA, providing savers with the flexibility to save towards a first home and retirement at the same time. From April 2017, people aged 18 to 40 will be able to open and save up to £4,000 each year into a Lifetime ISA and receive a 25% bonus from the Government, paid annually after the end of the tax year.</p><p>People can make full withdrawals from their Lifetime ISA accounts for a first home purchase (subject to a house price cap of £450,000 UK-wide) or from age 60. These withdrawals will be tax free.</p><p>The Lifetime ISA is a voluntary product. For further information on the costing of this policy, please see page 9 of the Budget 2015 Policy Costings document: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf</a> More than 350,000 first time buyers have opened a Help to Buy ISA since it became available.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-11T14:10:45.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484437/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484437/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-22","Individual Savings Accounts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of people likely to take up the lifetime ISA in the first year of its operation.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","32131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484438","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>The Government is always mindful of international comparisons when developing tax policy. In the case of the Lifetime ISA, the Government will explore with the industry whether there should be the flexibility to borrow funds from the Lifetime ISA without incurring a charge if the borrowed funds are fully repaid; for example, some US retirement plans allow 50% to be borrowed up to a maximum of $50,000.</p><p> </p><p>Further details about how the Lifetime ISA will work will be announced when the government brings forward legislation to enact the Lifetime ISA in the autumn.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-29T10:49:59.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484438/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484438/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-22","Individual Savings Accounts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he used any international systems to inform the formulation of his proposals to introduce a lifetime ISA.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","32096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484439","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Government has traditionally used a mix of terms to describe the groups we are working with on race equality: Black and Minority Ethnic (BME); Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic (BAME), also ethnic minority and minority ethnic.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-11T13:40:57.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484439/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484439/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-22","Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what definition her Department uses for BAME.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","32146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484440","Home Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Government published a new Violence Against Women and Girls strategy on 8 March committing £80 million between 2016 and 2020 to protect women and girls from violence and abuse. The increased funding will help to deliver our goal to work with local commissioners to ensure a secure future for rape support centres, refuges and the Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) and Forced Marriage Units, whilst driving a major change across all services which promote early intervention and prevention.</p><p>The strategy sets out how we will support local areas in implementing tailored services for victims who experience different forms of discrimination or additional barriers to accessing support. This includes the launch of a Service Transformation Fund from 2017 which will help to meet the needs of women and girls experiencing multiple disadvantage including victims from black and minority ethnic communities.</p><p>We continue to challenge the cultural attitudes that may underpin practices of FGM and forced marriage. We have criminalised forced marriage, set up a specialist FGM Unit, created a mandatory duty for frontline professionals to report FGM to the police, and will publish multi-agency FGM guidance for front-line professionals which we will put on a statutory footing.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-04-11T16:34:41.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484440/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484440/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-22","Crimes of Violence: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if her Department will bring forward policies to tackle violence against women and girls in the BAME communities.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","32150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484441","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-29","<p>The MQ-9 Users Group is a multilateral forum for France, Italy, the UK and US. As such, the release of the Group's Terms of Reference can only be approved if all four participating nations agree. To that end, the request for their release was highlighted at the MQ-9 User Group and individual nations will report back as soon as is practicable.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-03-29T14:56:34.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484441/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484441/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-22","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to Answer of 22 February 2016 to Question 26843, if he will publish the terms of reference for the Reaper User Group.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","32105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484442","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-29","<p>UK attendance at the MQ-9 User Group was limited to representatives from the Royal Air Force, led by the Intelligence, Surveillance, Target Acquisition and Reconnaissance Force Commander.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-03-29T14:57:03.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484442/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484442/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-22","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 23886, which UK representatives attended the meeting of the Reaper User Group between 14 and 18 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","32106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484443","Department of Health","false","2016-03-24","<p>The blood-borne virus (BBV) opt-out testing programme for people in prisons in England is a shared priority for Public Health England (PHE), NHS England and the National Offender Management Service. Programme implementation is overseen by a ‘tripartite’ Task-and-Finish Group which includes third sector and patient voice representation. The roll-out of the programme is informed by phased implementation and evaluation of ‘pathfinder prisons’ over three phases. Phase 1 began on 1 April 2014 and the formal evaluation was published on May 21 2015. Phase 2 pathfinder prisons began implementation from April 2015, with Phase 3 Pathfinders implementing from September 2015. BBV opt-out testing is not limited to only those prisons formally in the pathfinder programme.</p><p>NHS England estimates that currently 60% of the adult prison estate in England are offering opt-out testing and are confident that the target of implementation in every adult prison in England will be achieved by the end of the financial year 2016-17.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-24T16:09:26.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484443/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484443/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-22","Screening: Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of whether his target of implementing opt-out testing for blood-borne viruses in every adult prison in England by the end of financial year 2016-17 will be met.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","32094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484444","Department of Health","false","2016-03-24","<p>Implementation of opt-out testing for blood-borne viruses (BBVs) in all adult prisons in England in a shared priority for Public Health England (PHE), NHS England and the National Offender Management Service as published in our second National Partnership Agreement for 2015-16.</p><p>To support implementation, PHE and its partners, including The Hepatitis C Trust among other third sector organisations, have developed a broad range of range of resources to support prison healthcare teams. These include information leaflets and posters, testing algorithms, web-based and DVD resources which cover all aspects of prevention, diagnosis and treatment of Hepatitis C and other BBVs to support prison healthcare teams in offering testing, managing both positive and negative results, providing advice on harm minimisation and supporting people into treatment.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-03-24T16:07:50.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484444/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484444/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-22","Screening: Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has taken steps to provide national guidance to ensure that healthcare and wider staff in prisons are given adequate levels of training around blood-borne viruses as recommended by The Hepatitis C Trust's recent report, The blood-borne virus opt-out testing policy for prisons in England: An analysis of need towards full implementation, published on 3 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","32095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484445","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-11","<p>Responding to the food security situation in Ethiopia is a top priority. DFID has already committed £40 million to provide food aid to 3.8 million people in 2016, as part of its overall £113 million response since the onset of the drought last July.</p><p> </p><p>Across the country, 18 million people are in need of food assistance. Failed rains and the El Niño effect have caused the worst drought in Ethiopia in 30 years. This has resulted in reduced crop yields and numerous livestock deaths – increasing the country’s dependence on food aid.</p><p> </p><p>Plans are in place to provide monthly food rations until June from various sources, including the UN, donors, and the Government. The Government of Ethiopia has committed over $381 million (~£269 million) so far, which is its largest ever response to a drought. However, systems are currently stretched and the scale of the crisis means that further resources are needed to meet monthly food distribution needs from June onwards. We continue to work closely with the Government of Ethiopia to support their leadership of the humanitarian response.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-11T12:09:47.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484445/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484445/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-03-22","Ethiopia: Food Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 26 February 2016 to Question 27899, what recent assessment she has made of the food security situation in Ethiopia.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","32145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484446","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-11","<p>BIS’s investment in science capital projects supports the UK’s world class research base, which directly employed around 260,000 researchers in 2013 and delivers a significant return to the economy. Further jobs are supported by investment, for example through construction of advanced facilities or improved Science, Technology, Engineering and Maths skills. However, job creation is not the primary aim of science capital projects, and has not been measured for each project, so it is not possible to provide the information requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises that research is vital to our wellbeing and future economic success. This is why the science capital budget was increased to £1.1bn in 2015/16 and will rise with inflation to a total of £6.9bn over the period 2015 to 2021.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-11T16:24:18.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484446/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484446/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-22","Science: Job Creation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many jobs each of the 56 science capital projects his Department has funded since 2007 has created.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","32144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484447","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-11","<p>A BIS performance indicator showing the proportion of people aged 18-24 participating in full or part-time education or training broken down by social background defined by their father’s occupation is published online.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bis-performance-indicators-skills" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bis-performance-indicators-skills</a></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-11T14:54:36.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484447/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484447/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-22","Education: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of people between 18 and 24 from each social background defined by their father's occupation are participating in full or part-time education or training activity.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","32127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484448","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Student Loans Company (SLC) and HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) have spent the following on maintaining and collecting income contingent repayments since the financial year 2011-12:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Student Loans Company</p></td><td><p>HM Revenue and Customs</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FY 2011-12</p></td><td><p>£15.7m</p></td><td><p>£5.6m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FY 2012-13</p></td><td><p>£15.6m</p></td><td><p>£6.4m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FY 2013-14</p></td><td><p>£18.6m</p></td><td><p>£5.5m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FY 2014-15</p></td><td><p>£18.5m</p></td><td><p>£5.8m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FY 2015-16</p></td><td><p>£20.9m (forecast)</p></td><td><p>£6.3m (forecast)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The figures in the table above include both the direct costs and associated ICT and back office overheads incurred by SLC and HMRC in maintaining and collecting income contingent repayments.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-11T16:10:39.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484448/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484448/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-22","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the Student Loans Company and HM Revenue and Customs spent on maintaining and collecting student loan repayments in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","32087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484449","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) is considering the National Audit Office’s recent report on capital investment in science projects, and will respond in due course.</p><p> </p><p>All funding decisions are subject to BIS and HM Treasury’s rigorous scrutiny process and must pass a robust business case process before spending is approved.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-11T14:11:31.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484449/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484449/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-22","Science: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make it his policy to conduct a systematic analysis of existing science and research-based infrastructure in the UK for the purpose of guiding his Department's future investment priorities.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","32088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484450","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>From 26 May 2015, the maximum penalty for underpayment of the National Minimum Wage (NMW) increased from £20,000 per notice of underpayment (NoU) to £20,000 per worker.</p><p> </p><p>From 1 April 2016 the penalty has been increased to 200% of the total underpayment for all of the workers specified in a NoU. By increasing penalties for underpayment of the NMW it is intended that employers, who could otherwise be tempted to underpay, comply with the law and working people receive the money they are legally due. The maximum penalty will remain at £20,000 per worker.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-14T16:20:43.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484450/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484450/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/484450/answer/previousversion/54589","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-22","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what progress his Department has made on implementing its plans to impose financial penalties of up to £20,000 per worker against companies who fail to pay the national minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","32089"
